1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:29,000
Today is August 13th, 2013. This is David Klein speaking. I am a professor of history at Virginia Tech, also working for the Smithsonian Institute's National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

3
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:42,000
Today we are interviewing Judge D'Army Bailey here in Memphis, Tennessee. Behind the camera is John Bishop of UCLA and Media Generation.

4
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:46,000
We will begin now. Thank you so much for being part of this project.

5
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:50,000
I'm honored for the opportunity.

6
00:00:50,000 --> 00:01:01,000
As I started to say off camera, I wanted to start with a couple of questions before we get into the really Euro-bifestory and your story in the movement.

7
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:11,000
And if I could, the first question is, what is the difference between an activist and a radical?

8
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:24,000
An activist is a person who devotes energies to make and change to some project or some issue that that person is dedicated to.

9
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:38,000
A radical is a person who's also devoted in terms of their energies to make and change, but they are not bound by the same parameters that an activist is.

10
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:57,000
The radical sees beyond the acceptable barriers for action and conversation and bangs against the outer walls to make progress much farther than is institutionally conceived.

11
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:11,000
Now, being a realist, even though you're doing that and you're trying to open new horizons beyond acceptable boundaries, the end result is that you're lucky if you get to those walls.

12
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:22,000
But the activists, I think, short-sells themselves or herself by accepting the boundaries and therefore, because you're never going to achieve everything that you're seeking.

13
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:32,000
The radical, we posit concepts and agendas for change that in reality, we don't expect to achieve.

14
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:40,000
But we're dedicated to it, we fight for it as if we believe that we will and that's what keeps us going and makes dramatic change.

15
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:58,000
And I think you probably appreciate why I started asking you that question, especially because of the subtitle of your autobiography and I think, do you think of yourselves in those terms in terms of being both an activist and a radical or different things at different times or a radical?

16
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:21,000
Well, actually, I generally as two labels, we used that label for the book, the education of a black radical. And when I was in politics in California, I and the other two of my colleagues who were elected to the council were dubbed by the media as being radicals and it was called a radical takeover of the Berkeley, California City Government.

17
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:38,000
And so I've had that label attached to me. I have, I never used that myself in terms of definition when I was out there. And I really don't use it much today, but I do accept that that's a fair definition of me and my politics.

18
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:52,000
And I don't like labels, it's simply because it makes you more easily pigeonholed and therefore you're much easier target for those who want to discount what you're trying to do by attaching you with label.

19
00:03:52,000 --> 00:04:16,000
When I was involved in civil rights in Baden Rouge, my friends were in court, the Congress of Racism Quality and they were big supporters of what we were doing. But it took me the longest of time before I was willing to join court because I just don't personally like to associate myself with the denifiable groups where I can then be limited in terms of how people perceive me or what I can do.

20
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Right, right, very interesting. Thank you. And then the other big question I want to ask before we get into the biography is, how do you define the civil rights movement? I mean, our project here is called the Civil Rights History Project.

21
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:42,000
And there, there's a sort of traditional take on what the civil rights movement is, which is often bounded by or focused on Dr. Martin Luther King.

22
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:59,000
But I was very struck at the National Civil Rights Museum that you were a founder of, that the story, you begin the story much earlier, basically starting with the story of slavery and coming up to the very present day.

23
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:14,000
I'm interested in how you see the movement as a, is it a much longer battle on many fronts than we sometimes see in the history books as the 1955 to 1968.

24
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:33,000
Well, the earlier context going back to slavery and the abolitionist movement, I can't really claim a great deal of credit for envisioning that as a preliminary to the logic exhibits at the museum.

25
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:43,000
That was a broad context that was created in collaboration with some very excellent designers, including Benjamin Lawless, who had helped us to lay out much of the plan.

26
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:51,000
But I brought to the creation of the museum my experience in the civil rights movement.

27
00:05:51,000 --> 00:06:06,000
We had bought the Lorraine Motel at a foreclosure auction. I knew that it was a place that people would come from around the world because that's where Dr. King's blood still can be seen on the concrete walkway outside of the room where he last slept.

28
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:16,000
To me, it was a way of taking the magnetism of the death of King, but not creating a museum about King.

29
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:35,000
The museum that I wanted to create, and it was in large part the sense of my own experiences in the movement that helped to set the path for what the museum was to be because having come as a young college student in 1960 to the beginning of the time,

30
00:06:35,000 --> 00:07:02,000
the beginning of the city in Baton Rouge, and then having traveled down to Atlanta and visited with the snake leaders and been out into Rueville and sat down with Fannie Lou Hamer on our front porch and been at some of the great marches and dramatic scenes in Oven, Bogalusa, where the Deacon's for Defense and Justice had to meet us and escort us into town and protect us while we were there.

31
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:16,000
I knew the intensity of that movement, and I also knew that the Civil Rights Movement was not King. It was not any singular leader, even such a great person as a James Fama, who was equally very much important to that struggle.

32
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:39,000
But rather it was the combination of individuals, those young students that I saw who inspired me as another student who were willing to put the education on the line, to go to jail, to have their families worry about them, in some cases, their economic security being threatened, their families are security because their students were involved.

33
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:53,000
And I saw the courage of these people, and as I would go to these rallies and participate in them and hear the music, that's why we have an exhibit about the music of the Civil Rights Movement, the snake freedom singers.

34
00:07:53,000 --> 00:08:03,000
Of course, you know, Fannie Lou Hamer was a very great singer at these meetings. I've heard her sing and Pete Seeger and Pete Seeger.

35
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:23,000
And so all of that was a part of the spirit, even Anne Fagan and Braden, rather, and Carl Braden. Well Carl Braden, I came to meet when I was thrown out of school at Southern, and she was editing the Southern Patriot newspaper out of Kentucky.

36
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:47,000
She would send us words of encouragement and a few dollars here to help us. So it was a whole broad range of people that I saw Will D. Campbell up in from Mount Juliet, who recently passed, who was a mentor to me in helping to understand the spirit of human struggle.

37
00:08:47,000 --> 00:09:04,000
I spent about three weeks at the University of Wisconsin in 1961 at a Southern student here in relation to Seminaw, where there were 18 students, half black and half white, sponsored by the National Students Association.

38
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:26,000
And we were studying race issues, and we were bringing in speakers and Will D. Campbell and Connie Curry, whether two leaders of those sessions for us. And we got to know each other. Bob Zelner, for example, who later became a leader in SNCC, was one of my members of that group there at the University of Wisconsin.

39
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:43,000
So it was the process of learning, of studying, of being on the scene. And so to me the civil rights movement was the cold-dewon within which you had this extraordinary mix of spirit, of courage, of people from different backgrounds.

40
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:58,000
And most importantly, young blacks, we were the first generation from our families that went to college. And we didn't go off to college at these black state universities in the South with the intention of creating civil rights movement.

41
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:16,000
It was completely accidental that the movement happened in my first year of college, and that I became exposed to it. We went off to have a good time to educate ourselves for better opportunities in the world of business and growth.

42
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:30,000
But we were aware. And so I guess I'll also have to look back a little bit in terms of the definition of the movement because it was not just what happened in 1960 with the students at Greensboro.

43
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:43,000
I would remember as a young teenager sitting in a drug store where I delivered ice cream and things to people in the neighborhood on my bicycle, who would order it at the store.

44
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:53,000
But when I wasn't working there, I would sit and look at the magazine rack where we had jet magazine and ebony and black newspapers from Detroit and in the land of the daily world.

45
00:10:53,000 --> 00:11:05,000
And I would read about the civil rights movement and I saw the picture of Emmett Till when he'd been killed in his bloated body was exhibited in the cask at night.

46
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:18,000
And being in Memphis, which was so close to these hot spots of Mississippi, I saw those kids over in Little Rock at Central High School and the courage that they showed. And these were kids my age.

47
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:42,000
And so my civil rights movement, not as I defined it, but as it defined me, was a movement that started probably in the 1950s with the killing of Emmett Till with the students at Central High School in Little Rock with, you know, somewhat more distant way, the Montgomery Bus Borough Cot.

48
00:11:42,000 --> 00:12:02,000
And so when we were setting about to build the museum, the primary story, and that's why the exhibits there, the primary exhibits in the museum, start with the Central High School, well, it starts with Brown versus Peacock with a large exhibits there because the 54 decision was a pivotal one.

49
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:18,000
But I don't think that the 54 decision was the fuel that ignited the spirit of Black America. I think that the CNN Emmett Till's body and CNN's Black kids. Now, of course, that came as a result of the 54 decision.

50
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:30,000
But it was the hard work, the groundwork that had been done by Daisy Bates with the NAACP there in Little Rock who had the courage to help those kids to go to school, the courage of all of this movement.

51
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:38,000
And so, do you remember your actual reaction to that to them until photograph or your reaction, but also other people in the community?

52
00:12:38,000 --> 00:13:07,000
Quiet shock. I can't say that I was completely surprised. Nor was I overtaken with strong emotion about this because it was an education, it was a wake-up call, more than a shock, I guess.

53
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:20,000
It was a wake-up call that we've got some hell of a struggle ahead of us here if this is what they'll do to these young kids, to my people, to me. That this is serious business.

54
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:31,000
And so it detoured me very quickly as did what I saw those kids at Central High School do and go through.

55
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:44,000
It made quick men and women strong and it began to prepare us for what lay ahead.

56
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:48,000
It's interesting because you were young people who was happening to young people.

57
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:49,000
Yes.

58
00:13:49,000 --> 00:14:11,000
And it was no platitude to say it could happen to me. I would get on the bus when I was going to Southern and I'd take the train from Memphis to Hammond, Louisiana and get off there and then I'd have to take a bus from Hammond over to Baton Rouge.

59
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:21,000
And I would sometimes be sitting in the front section of the bus because I knew that the law was that they couldn't segregate me but I'd be the only black sitting up there in the front.

60
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:31,000
And then as the bus stopped in these little small towns and this was in 1960, 1961, why to get on and they would refuse to take the seats behind me.

61
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:39,000
And so they'd be standing in the aisles. And I would just be there in the seat and pretend that I was sleeping and just turning going about my business.

62
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:41,000
But I was an interstate bus.

63
00:14:41,000 --> 00:14:42,000
Interstate bus.

64
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:55,000
And because they would have signs in the bus stations that said whites, white women, white men and colored and the white sign actually would say whites and interstate passengers.

65
00:14:55,000 --> 00:15:03,000
But they'd also have signs that say colored and of course they didn't differentiate between colored men and colored women.

66
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:14,000
And so even though by law, since I was traveling from one state to the other they couldn't segregate me but in reality you were in quite some danger.

67
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:27,000
And I would even go on the buses from Baton Rouge to Atlanta at sometimes alone and why did that and where I had the courage to do that.

68
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:33,000
Because I could have easily ended up missing.

69
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:38,000
But maybe I was just crazy like that.

70
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:39,000
I don't know.

71
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:52,000
But I just felt that I was not born to lead my life letting fear overcome my dignity.

72
00:15:52,000 --> 00:15:57,000
It wasn't that I wasn't afraid. But it was the question of which would went out.

73
00:15:57,000 --> 00:16:05,000
And so as I would go into these places, I was shaking in my boots as it goes.

74
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:06,000
But they didn't know it.

75
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:09,000
Right. Right. Right. Couldn't have let them see that.

76
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:10,000
Yeah. Yeah.

77
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:15,000
Would you mind telling us a little bit about your your mother and father and the influence?

78
00:16:15,000 --> 00:16:18,000
Oh, I should have felt. I have a little time to say.

79
00:16:18,000 --> 00:16:22,000
We have to close the following once again, get some bigger and bigger in the Queen.

80
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:24,000
Anything happens who lose at all.

81
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:26,000
Yeah. So.

82
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:36,000
So if I could ask you to tell us a little bit about your your parents and their maybe their influence and in this regard.

83
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:44,000
And I I know a little bit about what they did for work and that there's a story there as well.

84
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:49,000
So I think about independent African Americans and the tradition of the Poland porters for example.

85
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:51,000
So could you tell us a little bit about that?

86
00:16:51,000 --> 00:16:56,000
Well, it was a struggle for both my mother and father, neither of whom finished high school.

87
00:16:56,000 --> 00:17:00,000
They got married while they were both in high school.

88
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:06,000
And so my daddy went to work with his father who was doing a building and repairing houses.

89
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:11,000
And my grandfather was sort of an entrepreneur after whom I'm named.

90
00:17:11,000 --> 00:17:13,000
And so in Tennessee?

91
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:21,000
Yes. Although he was born in Mississippi near Shelby County near the Tennessee Lion Act.

92
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:34,000
And so when I was growing up my mother was my earliest work that I remember her doing was as a housekeeper at a medical clinic with a doctor's office.

93
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:39,000
And they treated her very well. I mean they they treated her with respect.

94
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:44,000
She would even double as a receptionist at the clinic.

95
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:48,000
Although these were white doctors and their clientele was white.

96
00:17:48,000 --> 00:17:57,000
But she was basically a maid but she was respected and she carried herself with dignity when she was there at the clinic.

97
00:17:57,000 --> 00:17:59,000
And she worked with Dr. Seagerson.

98
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:02,000
And she was a DC Seagerson who was the physician.

99
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:09,000
And I remember that following her work at the clinic.

100
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:12,000
And we would go visit my brother and I sometimes.

101
00:18:12,000 --> 00:18:16,000
And we were again, we would treat it with respect.

102
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:22,000
My grandfather in addition to the work that he did in his own business, put me.

103
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:33,000
And grandfather, Papa as we called it, would work for two white women, sisters who were wealthy.

104
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:40,000
And they let him plant cotton on the back field of their yacht as well as peanuts.

105
00:18:40,000 --> 00:18:46,000
And so again they treated Papa with a great deal of respect.

106
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:51,000
And so my early experience, both in terms of my mother, my grandfather.

107
00:18:51,000 --> 00:18:56,000
My father, as I said, was working with my grandfather in those early years.

108
00:18:56,000 --> 00:19:02,000
Following the early work with his father, he started working for the railroad here in Memphis.

109
00:19:02,000 --> 00:19:05,000
He worked as a male handler.

110
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:10,000
So he would unload the mail from the trains onto Cots at the station.

111
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:18,000
He was able to initially get promoted up to work as a train porter, first pot time.

112
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:23,000
And then he got a full time position with Illinois Central Railroad.

113
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:28,000
And daddy worked the line from New Orleans to Chicago.

114
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:35,000
And so he'd get on the train here in Memphis and then he'd go Chicago and then back to New Orleans

115
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:38,000
and then come back and get off here at Memphis.

116
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:43,000
And as a result of him working with the railroad, we could travel free.

117
00:19:43,000 --> 00:19:47,000
My brother and I and my mother and of course my daddy.

118
00:19:47,000 --> 00:19:53,000
And so he would take my brother and me to foot, not to baseball games.

119
00:19:53,000 --> 00:19:58,000
Go to St. Louis and Chicago and Detroit.

120
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:05,000
He'd take us over to St. Louis and I saw some of the early black stars, Jackie Robinson and the R.I.P. now.

121
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:12,000
And we were just kids. We stayed in a little black hotel there in St. Louis.

122
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:20,000
My mother always respected the maturity of my brother, Walter and me.

123
00:20:20,000 --> 00:20:26,000
And so we had some latitude in terms of what we could do as young people.

124
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:34,000
We could go out at night and party and late and bar my dad is caught.

125
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:39,000
Because we acted responsibly.

126
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:47,000
She knew that both my brother and I were working with some black political people here

127
00:20:47,000 --> 00:20:55,000
doing political campaigns in the late 50s and early 60s, even as we were early on in college.

128
00:20:55,000 --> 00:20:58,000
And so there was no criticism of that.

129
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:01,000
Were they involved in all your parents?

130
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:05,000
Were they just supportive of your work activity?

131
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:10,000
No, they were not politically, I mean they were voters.

132
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:15,000
They were not organizationally active.

133
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:23,000
Now my mother was, she went back to school and got her GED.

134
00:21:23,000 --> 00:21:28,000
Then she got licensed as a Baba.

135
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:33,000
And so she was one of the first black female Babas in Memphis.

136
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:40,000
And then she did that for a short while, well, a short while, it was probably four or five years.

137
00:21:40,000 --> 00:21:46,000
And a Babishop in the center of the black neighborhood in South Memphis, Mississippi and Walker, where we grew up.

138
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:54,000
And after four or five years of cutting hair, she went back and got her license as a nurse

139
00:21:54,000 --> 00:22:03,000
and became a licensed practical nurse and worked first at what she was one of the first black nurses at St. Joseph Hospital here in Memphis.

140
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:10,000
And worked for many years, ultimately retiring from nursing.

141
00:22:11,000 --> 00:22:18,000
My father, he was an addition to being a train porter.

142
00:22:18,000 --> 00:22:26,000
He liked to play checkers and pools, so he had a lot of friends and he was outgoing.

143
00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:30,000
Very proud of his two sons.

144
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:37,000
But he was probably a bit more cautious, or savvy, I should say.

145
00:22:38,000 --> 00:22:46,000
And therefore, he didn't particularly urge us to be shaking at trees or rocking the boat.

146
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:55,000
I remember that when we would go down to the train station, again on the train, to go down to Baton Rouge.

147
00:22:55,000 --> 00:23:03,000
When you got to go up onto the train, the conductor would ask you, where were you going?

148
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:13,000
I would say Baton Rouge, Hammond, and they would say to the left, where the blacks were being sent, where the whites were being sent.

149
00:23:13,000 --> 00:23:16,000
So it didn't really matter where you were going.

150
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:23,000
But I would sometimes, if my father wasn't there, I'd go to the right and to the white section and sit down.

151
00:23:23,000 --> 00:23:32,000
But typically, if he was with me, my mother and I, then I wouldn't get them to upset about doing that.

152
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:40,000
But they knew that Walter and I, Walter was a football player and a very good one.

153
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:51,000
So he was with the jocks, to some extent, in the early years he later decided, in part, because of the civil rights efforts that were going on,

154
00:23:51,000 --> 00:23:56,000
and he had been put off campus when I was expelled from southern because of my activities.

155
00:23:56,000 --> 00:24:04,000
They lodged him in a dormitory of married students, number one were law students, and that's how you got interested in a career in law.

156
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:14,000
But my mother was supportive when I was expelled from southern in my junior year, and I called her and told her about it, and she was very calm.

157
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:20,000
She took things calmly, and my father did as well. He was very supportive.

158
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:37,000
But I guess it was the calmness and the serenity and elegance in some ways, quiet of my mother and the strength of my father.

159
00:24:37,000 --> 00:24:51,000
But she really kind of nurtured, I think, in her own way, not by advocacy, but by supporting us, the sense of independence that I developed and that my brother developed.

160
00:24:51,000 --> 00:24:59,000
And even before you went to southern, you were involved in some local organizations, right, with the NAACP and in Shelby County.

161
00:24:59,000 --> 00:25:06,000
Can you tell us a little bit about what those organizations were doing at that time?

162
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:27,000
The Memphis Blacks did not have a big challenge to vote in Memphis, because for many years in the 1940s and into the 1950s, Memphis was run by a political boss, one of the nations's premier bosses, E.H. "Boss" Crump.

163
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:33,000
And the Crump machine controlled politics not only in Memphis, but across the state of Tennessee.

164
00:25:33,000 --> 00:25:49,000
Part of his strength came from the Black vote. And so Crump would have certain people that were his lieutenants in the Memphis Black community that would help Corral and deliver the Black vote for him.

165
00:25:49,000 --> 00:25:58,000
These lieutenants would in turn be influential so that if Black people needed a job or needed some content, then they could go to these lieutenants.

166
00:25:58,000 --> 00:26:16,000
So the Blacks were able to vote in Memphis early on when the Crump machine went into its decline in the early 1950s, about the mid-50s, there was no longer a Crump machine, but you had a tradition of voting among Blacks.

167
00:26:16,000 --> 00:26:32,000
Now the NAACP was the premier Black political organization doing that time, composed of some Black business owners and professionals, but also a lot of Reik and Fowl Blacks were constituted in NAAC.

168
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:41,000
And that was about the only really noticeable civil rights group here, there wasn't a SNCC or a core as well at the time.

169
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:52,000
And the NA was a little bit more cautious in its strategies than some of the groups that emerged in the civil rights movement, such as core and SNCC.

170
00:26:52,000 --> 00:27:04,000
So to that extent, the thrust of the NAACP was into the political arena, working with a group of Black Democrats that formed the Shelby County Democratic Club.

171
00:27:04,000 --> 00:27:12,000
And that was the strongest Black political organization here, during the time that I was growing up as a teenager.

172
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:19,000
And so my brother and I worked as volunteers with the Democratic Club going to their meetings.

173
00:27:19,000 --> 00:27:29,000
We would go out on the sound trucks or to any elections and speak on the microphone and on the sound trucks and put out literature in the neighborhoods,

174
00:27:29,000 --> 00:27:35,000
origin votes for White candidates that were not segregationists.

175
00:27:35,000 --> 00:27:43,000
And those days we supported White candidates primarily on the basis of whether they were for or against racial segregation.

176
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:47,000
And these would have been liberals or moderates at the time.

177
00:27:47,000 --> 00:27:57,000
So the Democratic Club was very active in supporting those candidates and then began to support some trailblazing Black candidates.

178
00:27:57,000 --> 00:28:08,000
And so in the late 50s, there were at least a couple of Black candidates, Dr. Walker, J. Walker, who ran for the school board.

179
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:16,000
He was one of the leading Black businessmen and also Russell Sugarmon, who ran for the Commission of Public Works.

180
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:25,000
And that became sort of those races, particularly the Shigman race, became sort of caused celebrities because there was a good chance that Shigman could have won,

181
00:28:25,000 --> 00:28:41,000
except that the White community coalesced to force out some of the White candidates in order to focus their support around one who was Bill Ferris, because there was no runoff and they were fearful that if they didn't do that, Shigman would win.

182
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:50,000
So that became kind of, I guess, in a way my first introduction to the politics and also the politics of race.

183
00:28:50,000 --> 00:28:54,000
And they were inextricably bound together in the late 50s.

184
00:28:54,000 --> 00:29:07,000
And so Memphis, the way of civil rights in the late 50s was more of a political effort than it was openly race-based.

185
00:29:07,000 --> 00:29:15,000
So by the time I came through high school here and left in 59 off to college, Memphis was still sharply segregated.

186
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:21,000
The amusement park, we could only go to the amusement park on Tuesdays.

187
00:29:21,000 --> 00:29:27,000
And if the Tuesday was a holiday, then we couldn't go. We'd have to wait until the fall and we could go to White to go.

188
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:30,000
The same thing with the city zoo, we'd go on Thursdays.

189
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:38,000
And the schools were still segregated. The buses were segregated. So right on to the end of the 1950s,

190
00:29:38,000 --> 00:29:48,000
the racer had not been tackled directly here in Memphis as it had began to be tackled in say Montgomery with the bus for a card in 55 and 56.

191
00:29:48,000 --> 00:29:52,000
But even those White candidates that you described the Black community as...

192
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:53,000
I am.

193
00:29:53,000 --> 00:29:54,000
Perfect.

194
00:29:54,000 --> 00:29:55,000
Part two, part three.

195
00:29:55,000 --> 00:30:04,000
So even the White political candidates of the African American community did support because they weren't strict segregationists,

196
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:08,000
they weren't really dismantling the system.

197
00:30:08,000 --> 00:30:11,000
No, they were not.

198
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:19,000
But that was dramatic to have a commission candidate or to have a candidate for Senate, which we did.

199
00:30:19,000 --> 00:30:23,000
In fact, he won. He served only a short time.

200
00:30:23,000 --> 00:30:29,000
Ross Bass, a Democrat, a George W. Grider who won a seat for Congress.

201
00:30:29,000 --> 00:30:37,000
And again, they were not pro-segregationists. They were not pro-entit...

202
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:41,000
Well, they spoke in terms of the need for change.

203
00:30:41,000 --> 00:30:49,000
And that was all we could expect. But basically, they were not...

204
00:30:49,000 --> 00:30:53,000
Tilton had dramatic change in the system of racism that we saw here.

205
00:30:53,000 --> 00:30:57,000
But those were... But these were the baby steps that were necessary.

206
00:30:57,000 --> 00:31:03,000
And they were important to us at the time.

207
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:08,000
Okay. And so that was what's... The Shelby County Democratic Club.

208
00:31:08,000 --> 00:31:12,000
And the NAACP, was there a youth organization here in Memphis?

209
00:31:12,000 --> 00:31:14,000
No, not at that time.

210
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:17,000
That's why my brother and I, who were...

211
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:22,000
who were ordinarily in today's time, would have been part of the youth organization.

212
00:31:22,000 --> 00:31:26,000
And I think that it was good that there wasn't a youth organization.

213
00:31:26,000 --> 00:31:34,000
I mean, we were thrown in there with the seasoned strategist and we were in the meetings with them.

214
00:31:34,000 --> 00:31:38,000
And we were treated not as youth, but we were...

215
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:46,000
We were treated. In fact, one summer, I worked for the club and the sheriff...

216
00:31:46,000 --> 00:31:52,000
Sheriff Hines, who was a white sheriff here.

217
00:31:52,000 --> 00:32:00,000
I got paid for doing my work with the club by the sheriff's office because the club was supporting the sheriff.

218
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:04,000
And so he hired me as...

219
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:10,000
And I don't know, I might have gotten 40 dolls a week, which was an ice-low stipend.

220
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:18,000
And my job was to go out and find bootleggers and let them know who was selling corn whiskey out in the county areas.

221
00:32:18,000 --> 00:32:28,000
And so I'd go out to the bootleggers and buy a half-pain of corn liquor when every was time for me to go get my check and take it down there.

222
00:32:28,000 --> 00:32:34,000
And tell the sheriff they was still out there and give him my half-pain of whiskey and get my check and keep on going.

223
00:32:34,000 --> 00:32:38,000
But that was support. That was how...

224
00:32:38,000 --> 00:32:46,000
That was the nature of the give and take of our relationships that helped us to get things done.

225
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:52,000
So you had your eyes open to help politics really work out of young age.

226
00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:54,000
Yeah, very interesting.

227
00:32:54,000 --> 00:33:04,000
And so when you went on to college at Southern in Baton Rouge, you came down there as things were beginning to happen politically down there with some experience.

228
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:06,000
Yes.

229
00:33:06,000 --> 00:33:10,000
And in fact I ran for President of Freshman Class at Southern and was elected.

230
00:33:10,000 --> 00:33:20,000
And which was actually a good feat because I was now the state or most of the vast majority of the students at Southern were from Louisiana.

231
00:33:20,000 --> 00:33:26,000
And our class was probably about somewhere between 12 and 1500 students.

232
00:33:26,000 --> 00:33:34,000
So it gave me a forum and opportunity to speak out with the students.

233
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:43,000
And again, at the beginning when I was elected President of Freshman Class, it wasn't a civil rights agenda.

234
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:55,000
Although I was becoming aware of what was happening in South Africa because they had had the massacre in Johannesburg, which is a black activist.

235
00:33:55,000 --> 00:34:08,000
And so I was beginning to at least sense not just the national thrust of change, but the international by the drama of these people being massacred over there in South Africa.

236
00:34:08,000 --> 00:34:15,000
And I talked a little bit about that on campus. I wrote a column in the campus newspaper.

237
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:19,000
I didn't do that until my second year at Southern.

238
00:34:19,000 --> 00:34:32,000
But I was beginning to emerge, I guess, as a student leader on the campus, but not with any defined agenda.

239
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:37,000
But just working with other students to have nice parties.

240
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:44,000
I brought in a band from Memphis, which was great for the people in Baton Rouge, because they'd never seen a great rhythm in Blues band.

241
00:34:44,000 --> 00:34:56,000
Like I brought in, they came in with their trailers. I mean, I don't mean these big trailers. I mean, trailers on the back are cause of Gene Bollegs Miller and just put on a hell of a show there.

242
00:34:56,000 --> 00:35:01,000
I brought off the price stock to a period one of our dancers.

243
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:07,000
Because Walter and I, when we were teenagers, I mentioned that my parents would tolerate us going out.

244
00:35:07,000 --> 00:35:16,000
We'd actually go to some of the adults, I mean, some of the mature clubs, night clubs, and Drake Whiskey and listen to the music.

245
00:35:16,000 --> 00:35:21,000
But we would come back and we would handle ourselves responsibly.

246
00:35:21,000 --> 00:35:27,000
So I was already introduced to the entertainment circuit.

247
00:35:27,000 --> 00:35:33,000
And I just brought in some of those entertainers, at least like that band anyway, that I brought from Memphis.

248
00:35:33,000 --> 00:35:39,000
And of course, I didn't have any pre-biscontak with off the price stock, but we brought in there as well.

249
00:35:39,000 --> 00:35:44,000
So it wasn't just political that I was engaged in when I was at Southern.

250
00:35:44,000 --> 00:35:51,000
I was just, as I said, a student leader having a good time and enjoying Louisiana.

251
00:35:51,000 --> 00:35:57,000
It was a nice change for me, the environment, the students were at beautiful women.

252
00:35:57,000 --> 00:36:04,000
Southern had some of the most beautiful co-ets of any college on the black college circuit.

253
00:36:04,000 --> 00:36:09,000
And they had a great band, a Southern university band.

254
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:14,000
So it was a great experience for me in my first year there.

255
00:36:14,000 --> 00:36:16,000
And what year was that?

256
00:36:16,000 --> 00:36:17,000
59.

257
00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:18,000
59.

258
00:36:18,000 --> 00:36:19,000
Okay.

259
00:36:19,000 --> 00:36:22,000
Alright.

260
00:36:22,000 --> 00:36:26,000
And then Greensboro happened that month.

261
00:36:26,000 --> 00:36:27,000
Well, that February.

262
00:36:27,000 --> 00:36:29,000
Yeah, that spring, right?

263
00:36:29,000 --> 00:36:36,000
And I didn't know, but within a month or two of that, some students from Southern went and got arrested.

264
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:42,000
And we didn't know that we mean in most of the students that they were planning to do this.

265
00:36:42,000 --> 00:36:47,000
And that was a real eye-opener to us, not just that they'd gone down in and been arrested.

266
00:36:47,000 --> 00:36:55,000
But then when they were released on bond and got back to the campus and the administration chose to expel them from school.

267
00:36:55,000 --> 00:36:59,000
And this is, they had sat, can you tell us just a little bit about what they did?

268
00:36:59,000 --> 00:37:00,000
They sat in the room.

269
00:37:00,000 --> 00:37:04,000
Yeah, they went and sat in at some lunch counters in downtown Baton Rouge.

270
00:37:04,000 --> 00:37:05,000
And they were arrested.

271
00:37:05,000 --> 00:37:07,000
And Charles would disturb in a piece.

272
00:37:07,000 --> 00:37:15,000
In fact, the first group, Paul and the death, that led to the first US Supreme Court decision,

273
00:37:15,000 --> 00:37:22,000
a Gonaverse in the state of Louisiana, that affirmed the right of demonstrators and paved the way

274
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:29,000
for many of the subsequent demonstrators to proceed without being prosecuted.

275
00:37:29,000 --> 00:37:36,000
And the basis of the Gona case, Gonaverse in Louisiana, was that these Southern students had been arrested in downtown Baton Rouge.

276
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:41,000
And the state had accused them of disturbing the piece.

277
00:37:41,000 --> 00:37:47,000
And the Supreme Court decision was that, and the theory of disturbing the piece was that they were peaceful.

278
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:51,000
They went and sat at lunch counters, but that they would stir other people, white people up,

279
00:37:51,000 --> 00:37:54,000
who would attack them, and that was disturbing the piece.

280
00:37:54,000 --> 00:38:00,000
And the Supreme Court said in that decision, reversing the convictions because they were convicted at state level,

281
00:38:00,000 --> 00:38:04,000
that you cannot be convicted of disturbing the piece because you're a peaceful conduct

282
00:38:04,000 --> 00:38:08,000
for both someone else to engage in an unlawful conduct against you.

283
00:38:08,000 --> 00:38:14,000
And so that was a pioneer in case it came out of the first year of demonstrations there at Southern.

284
00:38:14,000 --> 00:38:20,000
I'll work some, yeah, you could charge someone with inciting a riot, I guess, by being peaceful.

285
00:38:20,000 --> 00:38:27,000
Yeah, in fact two Supreme Court decisions came out of two years later because the Gona decision was rendered.

286
00:38:27,000 --> 00:38:36,000
The kids were arrested in 1960, but the decision wasn't rendered until 1961, which was pretty quick for the Supreme Court.

287
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:42,000
But that came out in the autumn of 1961.

288
00:38:42,000 --> 00:38:47,000
And so later that fall, the students of Southern started demonstrating again.

289
00:38:47,000 --> 00:38:56,000
And I was then part of a large demonstration of students that marched into downtown Baton Rouge in December of 1961.

290
00:38:57,000 --> 00:39:04,000
And we were tear gasped and dogs were set upon us, and some of our leaders were arrested.

291
00:39:04,000 --> 00:39:10,000
And one of our leaders who had been an organizer for the Congress of Race and Quality, Reverend Rev. B. Elton Cox,

292
00:39:10,000 --> 00:39:13,000
was arrested there that day.

293
00:39:13,000 --> 00:39:22,000
And that led to a second Supreme Court decision, Cox v. Louisiana, in which the Supreme Court reversed the Cox conviction.

294
00:39:23,000 --> 00:39:33,000
And the accused Reverend Cox violating a Louisiana law that said that he couldn't demonstrate in a courthouse, that he would be intimidation.

295
00:39:33,000 --> 00:39:39,000
And the Supreme Court actually went through some, it was a divided opinion of the court.

296
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:46,000
And they ended up reversing the conviction by saying that, well, he actually had permission of the police.

297
00:39:47,000 --> 00:39:54,000
And I know that he didn't have permission of the police because we got stopped twice.

298
00:39:54,000 --> 00:40:03,000
And the first time the police officers told him, my brother and I were right at head of the line with Reverend Cox, as we formed around the old state capital in Baton Rouge.

299
00:40:03,000 --> 00:40:10,000
And we were getting ready to march, and the police captain came over and spoke to Reverend Cox and said, turn these students around.

300
00:40:10,000 --> 00:40:15,000
And he said, well, we came here to march and we're going to be peaceful. So we started out to march and they stopped him again.

301
00:40:15,000 --> 00:40:21,000
And they said, now you've had your say, now I'm going to have nine, I want you to turn these students around.

302
00:40:21,000 --> 00:40:24,000
And Cox said, we're going to proceed to jail, we're peaceful.

303
00:40:24,000 --> 00:40:34,000
And so he stopped him twice. Well, the Supreme Court took that as being that he had gotten permission to carry on the demonstration at the courthouse.

304
00:40:34,000 --> 00:40:53,000
Well, he was violating the order of the police, what he was doing. But they let us go on to the, because at that point they either could break us up and start arresting us or let us go on to the courthouse to jail because it was both the jail and courthouse.

305
00:40:53,000 --> 00:41:04,000
And we were really going to the protest because our students were in jail down there. But the arrests was based on the fact that we were at a courthouse.

306
00:41:04,000 --> 00:41:08,000
And that was a state law? Yeah. And so that changed that.

307
00:41:08,000 --> 00:41:21,000
Right. And so that changed that. Well, yes, well, it changed it. I don't know. It didn't really, the court danced around it because as judges themselves, they didn't want to hold the court.

308
00:41:21,000 --> 00:41:32,000
So that's why they did this, this flip flop about, well, he had the permission. So it really wasn't a violation of the statute.

309
00:41:32,000 --> 00:41:36,000
Okay. So they didn't say also the statute. No, they didn't over turn the statute.

310
00:41:36,000 --> 00:41:39,000
Very interesting.

311
00:41:39,000 --> 00:41:45,000
Yeah. Because of course the courthouse is a potent symbol and a commonplace to demonstrate. Yes.

312
00:41:45,000 --> 00:41:56,000
And the court one, you could tell from the opinion, if you ever read Cox v. Louisiana that they certainly didn't want to say that you could come up on the courthouse steps and protest.

313
00:41:56,000 --> 00:42:00,000
Right. Right.

314
00:42:01,000 --> 00:42:11,000
So you were involved in those protests and the result of your involvement in that was what? Absolutely.

315
00:42:11,000 --> 00:42:29,000
Well, by the time of my junior year, because the first wave of protests that happened in 1960 upon the, in the wake of the Greensboro Cityans, did not yield any breakdown in segregation.

316
00:42:29,000 --> 00:42:37,000
The restaurants continued segregated. And things quieted down because the expulsion of the student leaders continued.

317
00:42:37,000 --> 00:42:51,000
That summer was really my first venture outside of the South where I was in an interracial setting when I went to the National Convention of the United States National Students Association as one of the two delegates from Southern.

318
00:42:51,000 --> 00:42:57,000
And these were student leaders from around the country, black and white, including many from the South.

319
00:42:57,000 --> 00:43:07,000
And there was a great debate going on at that convention because the Southern schools were mad that the leadership of the National Student Association had endorsed the city in movement.

320
00:43:07,000 --> 00:43:17,000
And they wanted to reverse that decision. And so the entire convention was overwhelmed with the debate about whether to support the city in movement.

321
00:43:17,000 --> 00:43:34,000
And which the convention ultimately did. But here I was on this campus with some of the best student leaders, both conservative and liberal from across the country, arguing about the issue of the city in protest and not to provide.

322
00:43:34,000 --> 00:43:40,000
This was where I got at the University of Minnesota on the campus of the University of the summer of 1960.

323
00:43:40,000 --> 00:44:01,000
And that's where I got to meet people like Alut and Einstein and Tom Hayden, Barney Frank was a student in Hobbit at the time in one of the outspoken supporters of the city in movement fighting against the Southern schools that wanted to reverse the endorsement.

324
00:44:01,000 --> 00:44:30,000
I mentioned that because not only was this my exposure to white activists, but it also was for me anyway the pivotal chance to see that the student activism, you see, it was a whole different climate at that time.

325
00:44:30,000 --> 00:44:41,000
Not just black students now, but white students, National Student Association was a strong national organization based in Philadelphia that had a budget.

326
00:44:41,000 --> 00:44:48,000
It had a lobbyist in Washington that was working to lobby Congress on issues that the students took positions on.

327
00:44:48,000 --> 00:44:57,000
And then, Alut and Einstein, who later went to Congress, was one of the sort of he wasn't a student at the time, but he was very close to the students.

328
00:44:57,000 --> 00:45:05,000
And he was sort of one of the liaison between the student association. So we had a national student group there.

329
00:45:05,000 --> 00:45:23,000
NSA also had its international wing that was called the, well, it was the international division, which later was associated in some kind of support from the CIA and it was an embarrassment to the NSA from that.

330
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:46,000
But the national section of the NSA was not caught up in that. But I saw in my two years of conventions at the NSA some of the, again, some of the great issues and debates at the time that was when Huwack, there was a big debate about the House Committee on Un-American activities.

331
00:45:46,000 --> 00:45:58,000
And they had had the demonstrations out there and there was a film that was put out by Fulton Lewis III, an attempted to brand all of the activists as communist.

332
00:45:58,000 --> 00:46:07,000
I can't remember this film now, but they were going around the country trying to persuade people that this was all a communist plan among the students.

333
00:46:07,000 --> 00:46:18,000
They were all great debate on the Wisconsin campus in the summer of 61, the following year after I had done this seminar there.

334
00:46:18,000 --> 00:46:34,000
So I mentioned those things to say that by the time I was in my junior year at Southern, my horizon had expanded in terms of understanding the national and even the international dimension, but particularly the national dimensions of this movement.

335
00:46:34,000 --> 00:46:44,000
And it was not just then confined to the energy of Southern black students, but it was confined to the supportive energy of white students from different parts of the country.

336
00:46:44,000 --> 00:46:51,000
And so I could see a strong movement that I knew was there at last and it did last.

337
00:46:51,000 --> 00:47:02,000
And so I came out of NSA, came the Port Huron meeting of the students and the formation of the students of the Democratic Society.

338
00:47:02,000 --> 00:47:08,000
In fact, I have one of the original Port Huron statements among my papers.

339
00:47:08,000 --> 00:47:23,000
And that was of course the statement by those who gathered at the Port Huron Michigan to give sort of their treaties on the things that needed to be changed to America.

340
00:47:23,000 --> 00:47:33,000
So again, if you think in the context of what makes a radical, those who gathered at Port Huron informed the students of the Democratic Society.

341
00:47:33,000 --> 00:47:59,000
And again, I knew many of these people. I wasn't at Port Huron, but I was close enough to these people in their thinking and my associations with them, not just at these conventions, but in later meetings because I would go back to when I was in Massachusetts up to Yale and we would meet on the campus there and student leaders would come from different parts of the North together.

342
00:47:59,000 --> 00:48:14,000
But when I was in my junior year at Southern, protest broke out again by the time of that decision and the Cox case and Cox was arrested and prosecuted and that was in December of 61.

343
00:48:14,000 --> 00:48:23,000
And the president closed the school, the president of university and ordered everybody home early for the holidays.

344
00:48:23,000 --> 00:48:32,000
When the school reopened, we still had a number of about 20 of our students still in jail that had caused us to go down and protest to begin with.

345
00:48:32,000 --> 00:48:42,000
And so we started a boardcott on the campus because we wanted to be assured that these students were not going to be expelled.

346
00:48:42,000 --> 00:49:03,000
And so we started rallies and the administration asked us not to do that. And they called me to the Dean of Men's office one night, my brother and me, and the Dean of Men talked to me and told me that if I spoke at the rally that we had planned the next rally, that I was going to be expelled from the university.

347
00:49:03,000 --> 00:49:19,000
And so I spoke and they called me to the Dean of Men's office within a day or so. And the Dean of Men and Dean of Students talked to me and gave me a letter, expelled me from the university.

348
00:49:19,000 --> 00:49:35,000
And simultaneously, with the time that they had me in this meeting, the president of the university had called a campus-wide assembly of students in the gymnasium and announced that because of the ongoing protest that he was going to close the school.

349
00:49:35,000 --> 00:49:42,000
And that all students had to be off campus by 5 o'clock. This was a new new rally.

350
00:49:42,000 --> 00:49:58,000
And so you've got students there from all over the state of Louisiana who don't know how to get back home. They've got to make combinations, got to get money, they got to contact their parents. And it was hectic and very scary to many of these students.

351
00:49:58,000 --> 00:50:11,000
I didn't know quite what was going on because as I said, they had me in the Dean of Students office. They had it made this letter and it said that my connection with the university was being handed.

352
00:50:11,000 --> 00:50:21,000
They said, I violated rule 18. And it was a rule in the university handbook that was entitled, lack of university adjustment.

353
00:50:21,000 --> 00:50:33,000
And the rule read that the university reserves the right to sever a student's connection for general inability to adjust to the patterns of the institution period.

354
00:50:33,000 --> 00:50:36,000
And however they interpret that.

355
00:50:36,000 --> 00:50:51,000
Well, as I was told that this was a rule that they were using when students were homosexuals to expel them. But most of the students who had been in the movement, you see, they were expelled from them because they'd been arrested. Well, I hadn't been arrested at that time.

356
00:50:51,000 --> 00:50:58,000
And so the only rule that they could find that they could use to justify my expulsion was this rule 18.

357
00:50:58,000 --> 00:51:18,000
And so with that expulsion, actually I did not leave campus that night. I stayed in my dorm because a lot of the students actually couldn't literally get off campus at night, but the campus was on lockdown.

358
00:51:18,000 --> 00:51:29,000
And we soon thereafter had to move off campus into a black hotel in downtown Baton Rouge and were banned from coming to the university campus.

359
00:51:29,000 --> 00:51:38,000
So that must have sewn all sorts of, I mean, you talk about the chaos of everyone having to leave, but then that's so sort of recrimination, I would think among the students too.

360
00:51:38,000 --> 00:51:41,000
Yes.

361
00:51:41,000 --> 00:51:51,000
And there was confusion because when President Clark announced that the school was closing, he told the students we don't know when the school is going to reopen.

362
00:51:51,000 --> 00:51:58,000
And we'll send you if you're to come back, we'll send you a letter. If you don't get a letter, don't come.

363
00:51:58,000 --> 00:52:10,000
And so it wasn't just in a matter of those students because some other students, those who had been arrested and a handful of other leaders were explicitly told that they were expelled.

364
00:52:10,000 --> 00:52:22,000
But many students were not told that they were expelled. They just did not get a letter to come back to the university. It opened about two weeks after Dr. Clark called. I think it was about 10 days that he reopened the university.

365
00:52:22,000 --> 00:52:39,000
And in the meantime, we were trying to keep the boycott going and trying to get kids. And three of us who had been expelled took a taxi from downtown back to the campus to make a stand by attempting to register.

366
00:52:39,000 --> 00:52:52,000
And the police quickly surrounded us on the campus. And fortunately for us, one of the university's security put us in a car and drove us to the edge of campus as we were followed by Louisiana Troopers.

367
00:52:52,000 --> 00:52:59,000
Otherwise, we had been arrested on the campus, but they didn't want us to be arrested at that time, so they drove us off the campus.

368
00:52:59,000 --> 00:53:08,000
But that was how determined they were to quell any continuing protests. And they did. They killed the movement. At least they killed it for time.

369
00:53:08,000 --> 00:53:15,000
There. Yeah.

370
00:53:15,000 --> 00:53:29,000
Now, how devoted were you to the concept of nonviolence in your protest there and did you ever think about other options, other ways of protesting?

371
00:53:29,000 --> 00:53:46,000
We really, it really wasn't a choice. To me, the whole concept of nonviolence was for us really more of an academic issue because strategically you didn't have much choice but to be nonviolent.

372
00:53:46,000 --> 00:53:58,000
I mean, if you're going into a lunch counter or as we were, three thousand of us marching from the campus to downtown Baton Rouge and they've got police dogs and they've got tear gas.

373
00:53:58,000 --> 00:54:04,000
It didn't make any sense to be violent. How you got to fight back with something like that? All you could to.

374
00:54:04,000 --> 00:54:19,000
So yes, we were strategically, we were all well dressed, orderly. And even as we ran with the gas and with the dogs, we tried to maintain some decor among ourselves.

375
00:54:19,000 --> 00:54:38,000
But I would go as I said periodically down. In fact, I was, I was hold up in this black hotel in downtown Baton Rouge where we stayed for, oh, I'd guess, three, four weeks trying to carry our movement on and our bill was being paid by the National Office of Coa.

376
00:54:38,000 --> 00:55:01,000
And so, SNCC, Student and Monocording Committee, one of the leaders that had gotten us stirred up in this second wave of protest was a young man by the name of Dion Diamond who had come to Baton Rouge, but Dion was a SNCC organizer that came to the Southern campus.

377
00:55:01,000 --> 00:55:15,000
Now, there were organizers from New Orleans who had been with the Congress of Racial Equality who also involved. Well, Dion was arrested quickly for his coming on the campus, speaking and raising help.

378
00:55:15,000 --> 00:55:29,000
So because Dion was in jail, we were out of school, we were down at the black hotel, a SNCC sent in to Baton Rouge to his field secretaries, Chuck McDew and Chuck McDew.

379
00:55:29,000 --> 00:55:48,000
And well, Bob, I had known from, we were both at the Seminole at the University of Wisconsin the year before. And so, they came and checked in at the Lincoln Hotel where we were and they were going to visit Dion at the jail.

380
00:55:48,000 --> 00:56:03,000
And they went down to see Dion and they were arrested. They looked into Bob and Chuck's precades and found some literature and stuff and accused him of criminal anarchy and sedition and arrested them.

381
00:56:03,000 --> 00:56:16,000
And so, because of that involvement of the SNCC leaders, I then started going to Atlanta for some of the SNCC staff meetings.

382
00:56:16,000 --> 00:56:30,000
And that's how I initially got to know John Lewis and Julian Bond, Julian was editing the SNCC newsletter, the student voice, and John was active in SNCC and Jim Foreman was the national director.

383
00:56:30,000 --> 00:56:45,000
And so, I went to a couple of the SNCC meetings in Atlanta from Baton Rouge and some of the core people, Dave Dennis being one of them who was a core field secretary who was staying with us at the hotel but hadn't been a student.

384
00:56:45,000 --> 00:57:06,000
And they were suspicious of what I was doing going to Atlanta meeting with the SNCC people. And I had a joint core. We created our own student organization called Student Action Committee, I think, because I just didn't want to be identified with a formal group.

385
00:57:06,000 --> 00:57:14,000
And so, at one point they even looked at my mail that was coming from SNCC to see what kind of correspondence was going on.

386
00:57:14,000 --> 00:57:34,000
Now, I mentioned that as an aside only to suggest that there were some rivalries. Now, I wasn't part of those rivalries because there was nothing sinister of one group plotting against the other but there was just that sort of group, I guess, self-protectiveness of turf, I guess, or whatever you want to call it.

387
00:57:34,000 --> 00:58:03,000
And I was not a part of that. But by doing that, by getting to know some of the SNCC people, it expanded my base of contact with the movement because by the time I left Southern and went to school in Massachusetts, the Northern Student Movement, which was run by Peter Countryman, a young white student up in Yale, had been formed by Peter and some of his people, Thomas K. Gilhool and some others.

388
00:58:03,000 --> 00:58:30,000
It was based there, and so I would go over from Worcester to Yale to some of the Northern Student Movement meetings. Well, because Northern Student Movement was so closely aligned as a support group in the North for SNCC, then the SNCC leaders would come up to the Yale campus for some meetings. And so I would go over to the New Haven. In fact, I started a chapter of the Northern Student Movement in Worcester.

389
00:58:30,000 --> 00:58:40,000
And we started to do it in Worcester. And we started to do it in and having some anti-discrimination demonstrations against some businesses in Worcester.

390
00:58:40,000 --> 00:58:43,000
Now, how did you end up at Clark?

391
00:58:43,000 --> 00:58:53,000
Rather by circumstance, I guess after I was expelled from Southern, I was at the Lincoln Hotel.

392
00:58:54,000 --> 00:59:09,000
We filed a lawsuit to try to get back in. We sued in federal court with lawyers from COA, law firm out of New Orleans, Collins Douglas in Eli, which was a black law firm that was helping us.

393
00:59:09,000 --> 00:59:19,000
And they made a compromise with the university that they would let most of the students that had been expelled back. There were two of us that they would not take back.

394
00:59:19,000 --> 00:59:24,000
And that was me and Ronnie Moore, who was one of the other student leaders.

395
00:59:24,000 --> 00:59:44,000
And I was told that the president was mad at me because I had called up to his house one day when we were a group of us student protesters wanted to meet him, meet with him.

396
00:59:44,000 --> 00:59:58,000
And I couldn't get him on the phone. And I think I might have spoken to Mrs. Clark. And I said, I mean, I'm not sure. But I said, if he won't meet with, we'll just come up there to the house.

397
00:59:58,000 --> 01:00:13,000
And so it may have been his office. I'm not sure. But in any event, I'm told that he was angry about my rudeness in that encounter because I remember that we ended up marching to his house.

398
01:00:13,000 --> 01:00:28,000
That was a little bit later, I think, because we had an all night vigil on his lawn. But this was also before we had been expelled. So Dr. Clark apparently was pretty clear that he didn't want me back.

399
01:00:28,000 --> 01:00:41,000
So they settled the lawsuit and it didn't bother me that they settled it and said that why would it come back because maybe by that time I already had to offer to go to clock. I'm not sure.

400
01:00:41,000 --> 01:00:53,000
That came because Walter Williams, who was a black student at Jackson State in Mississippi, was in the seminar with me at the university was constant the previous summer.

401
01:00:53,000 --> 01:01:08,000
And so Walter had been offered a scholarship to go to clock because he'd been expelled as student by the president at Jackson State. And he said, well, I'm going to go into military, but contact my friend, D'Army Bailey and Baton Rouge.

402
01:01:08,000 --> 01:01:18,000
He's been kicked out of school there. So they contacted me while I was at the hotel there in Baton Rouge and offered me a scholarship to go to clock. I didn't know anything about the university. Never heard of it.

403
01:01:18,000 --> 01:01:28,000
And so I looked at the catalog and saw these white kids and this completed alien look of environment to me.

404
01:01:28,000 --> 01:01:37,000
But you know, it was a, I could tell it was a good school and I didn't have one in any other school.

405
01:01:37,000 --> 01:01:48,000
Right. And so I came back to Memphis and then I had to take the SAT test here in order to, I mean, I'd been admitted to clock, but I had to take the SAT.

406
01:01:48,000 --> 01:02:09,000
And then last I went to, what is now Rhodes College, which is just a block away. And I took that that summer before I went to clock. I mentioned that because at the lunch break, the test administrators came over to me and pulled me aside and they said that I couldn't have lunch with the rest of the students who would take the test.

407
01:02:09,000 --> 01:02:23,000
So two or three of them, very nicely, I mean, they were nice about it, but they took me into the faculty dining hall on the side and I had dinner with lunch with a couple of them because I couldn't with the, and this was in 1962.

408
01:02:23,000 --> 01:02:35,000
But I took the SAT and then at fall, I went on to clock. Well, how did it, how did it come about was that a number of student leaders in the South were being expelled.

409
01:02:35,000 --> 01:02:53,000
And so this was a gesture made on the led by students at clock University to raise money and they had car washes and bake sales and the like and they raised a couple of thousand dollars in the University made a chip in a little bit and offered a scholarship to some students who had been expelled from the Southern School.

410
01:02:53,000 --> 01:02:56,000
And consequently, that's how I ended up there.

411
01:02:56,000 --> 01:03:01,000
Was there other schools that were doing some more things? I've never heard of that. How's that happening?

412
01:03:01,000 --> 01:03:15,000
I don't know. I do know that Senator Jabbits made note of the clock effort in the Senate records there because it was announced in just your own there part at the time.

413
01:03:15,000 --> 01:03:26,000
So you, and as you mentioned, it was a bit of a different world that you entered into in Worcester coming from Tennessee and also Louisiana.

414
01:03:26,000 --> 01:03:46,000
I didn't know really what to expect. I mean, I knew I had a free train ride because my father could get the pass to ride up to Massachusetts. I'd have to go all the way up through upstate New York because I had to follow the route that Illinois Central had partnership with New York Central.

415
01:03:46,000 --> 01:03:58,000
And so I would go to Chicago and then Chicago up through Pekipsi and Buffalo and all those places to ultimately get to Boston. Well, actually to Wister.

416
01:03:58,000 --> 01:04:05,000
And when I got there, the school had picked out two nice students to Bob.

417
01:04:05,000 --> 01:04:13,000
I have trouble with him in his last name. I think it was Miller and Fred Jealous and they met at the train station.

418
01:04:13,000 --> 01:04:27,000
They had an apartment that I was to share with him. And so they took me over. Fred, by coincidence, is the father of Ben Jellis now the national head of the NA.

419
01:04:27,000 --> 01:04:38,000
But I was I room with them for the first year that I was there in the apartment, which was right in a building owned by the university.

420
01:04:38,000 --> 01:04:45,000
And could you have lived on campus? Was that an option? Yes, it was, I think.

421
01:04:45,000 --> 01:04:58,000
But I think the university was wanting to create an environment for me with two, I guess, volunteers or nice students, nice little, I mean, what?

422
01:04:58,000 --> 01:05:05,000
Fans, they've had a nice apartment. So it never came up. I mean, they had placed for me when I got there.

423
01:05:05,000 --> 01:05:12,000
So I just went and I remember my 21st birthday party. They gave me a fifth of Jack Daniels.

424
01:05:12,000 --> 01:05:27,000
You know, so they were nice. When I first got to clock, students were, of course, I was something of a cost of labor because I was the one that they had raised the money to bring up there.

425
01:05:27,000 --> 01:05:37,000
And kids would want to talk to me about the South. And initially I would talk to them about the South and Civil Rights and the like.

426
01:05:37,000 --> 01:05:46,000
And then I got tired of it. I got tired of just talking about race in the South. And I started asking them about what was going on in Worcester.

427
01:05:46,000 --> 01:05:52,000
Well Worcester didn't have a large black community. It was only about 3,000 out of like a couple hundred thousand people.

428
01:05:52,000 --> 01:06:02,000
But that black community that they had was in a segregated area of the city. And there was not much interaction of that community with the rest of the community as I said.

429
01:06:02,000 --> 01:06:15,000
Departments to a downtown didn't have any black clerks. The big factory there, Wyman-Gordon, which was run by National Secretary of the John Burst Society, had 18 black employees and they were all janitors.

430
01:06:15,000 --> 01:06:27,000
So I started, so I went over to the Yale campus and getting support to start this Worcester student movement, this WSM chapter on the clock campus.

431
01:06:27,000 --> 01:06:37,000
I drew in students, liberal white students from the campus, as well as a handful of people from the black community in Worcester.

432
01:06:37,000 --> 01:06:48,000
And we formed a group and started having meetings. We began tutoring the main mission of Northern Student Movement, part of this mission was to tutor kids and intercity neighborhoods.

433
01:06:48,000 --> 01:07:02,000
And so we had volunteers that were tutoring those kids. How about if it in Worcester was created an organization called Prospect House, which is now an ongoing community institution of some importance to Worcester.

434
01:07:02,000 --> 01:07:14,000
Abbie Hoffman was living in Worcester at the time and had come out of Brandeis and needed a cause and he attached himself to our efforts.

435
01:07:14,000 --> 01:07:25,000
Even though he was a student, but he was living there and he became sort of self-appointed publicist for us, putting out a newsletter called The Drum.

436
01:07:25,000 --> 01:07:33,000
And we came by meetings. But we were primarily students and members of the Worcester black community.

437
01:07:33,000 --> 01:07:41,000
And we set about the business of finding out what was happening on the job front with the Noides.

438
01:07:41,000 --> 01:07:54,000
And we did tackle the largest industrial employer in Worcester, Wyman Gordon company, which was, say, was run by Robert W. Stoddard, who was the national secretary of John Birch, society.

439
01:07:54,000 --> 01:08:01,000
We met with him and asked him about his employment of blacks and whether he would promote him.

440
01:08:01,000 --> 01:08:12,000
And he said that in essence, no. And so we picketed his plant, brought the plant to a stop at least for one day because the teamsters wouldn't cross our picket line.

441
01:08:12,000 --> 01:08:20,000
And I filed complaints with the Massachusetts commission against discrimination and the defense department because they were a big defense contractor.

442
01:08:20,000 --> 01:08:30,000
And investigations were undertaken by both agencies in which they found some cause and demanded to a required that the plant undergo some change.

443
01:08:30,000 --> 01:08:41,000
So this was a case of not only where we put in pressure, starting as just a group of young activists, but we were putting pressure on this big factory.

444
01:08:41,000 --> 01:08:51,000
And Stoddert was not just a owner of Wyman Gordon, he also owned the Worcester Telegram in Gazette, which was the local newspaper and radio station at WTAG.

445
01:08:51,000 --> 01:08:53,000
And was on the board of clock.

446
01:08:53,000 --> 01:08:54,000
It's in a lot of power.

447
01:08:54,000 --> 01:08:55,000
Yes, but clearly.

448
01:08:55,000 --> 01:09:05,000
In fact, the president of clock called me in just a day of our picket and was gently trying to dissuade us. He wasn't heavy handed about it.

449
01:09:05,000 --> 01:09:13,000
But by that time, when I called over to the picket line, they already started.

450
01:09:13,000 --> 01:09:23,000
And so I had a good out with Dr. Jefferson that I couldn't stop it because it was already started.

451
01:09:23,000 --> 01:09:40,000
But we, I mentioned the multifaceted strategy, picketing, but also those complaints with the Massachusetts Commission and with the defense department.

452
01:09:40,000 --> 01:09:47,000
So here we were using multifaceted strength against this corporation and made them change.

453
01:09:47,000 --> 01:09:54,000
And it was clear to me that you can as a small force.

454
01:09:54,000 --> 01:10:02,000
But if you use the right strategies and do your research and know where the vulnerabilities are, you can force corporations to change.

455
01:10:02,000 --> 01:10:04,000
And that's what we did in Worcester.

456
01:10:04,000 --> 01:10:14,000
When I graduated, there was an editorial in the student newspaper that said, one is enough.

457
01:10:14,000 --> 01:10:23,000
And the editor was talking about that some students had talked about having another campaign to raise funds to bring a student from the south.

458
01:10:23,000 --> 01:10:29,000
And they said, we've had that experience once before and he found racial problems under every rock, so to speak.

459
01:10:29,000 --> 01:10:32,000
And we don't need to do that again.

460
01:10:32,000 --> 01:10:48,000
And the next issue of the clock paper, though, was had a page full of letters in opposition and in support of that I wasn't really that terrible for us on the clock campus.

461
01:10:48,000 --> 01:10:55,000
Clock gave me an honorary doctorate of laws three years ago.

462
01:10:55,000 --> 01:11:01,000
Now, you know, this is okay.

463
01:11:01,000 --> 01:11:17,000
I'm curious about, you know, we're now in the north and it's a couple of years later, you had been talking about the sort of the very real sort of fear and intimidation that was so prevalent in the south when you first went down to southern.

464
01:11:17,000 --> 01:11:25,000
Well, was the situation like that you found a few years later in up north around the park and in Worcester.

465
01:11:25,000 --> 01:11:34,000
And what gave you the strength to do things like challenge the national director or the town versus I?

466
01:11:34,000 --> 01:11:41,000
I didn't have much fear in Worcester.

467
01:11:41,000 --> 01:11:46,000
And the position to what we were doing was there wasn't any visible.

468
01:11:46,000 --> 01:11:54,000
There were some students actually from the clock campus who counterpicked it against us when we picketed the plant.

469
01:11:54,000 --> 01:12:10,000
But the police in charge, Sergeant, at the scene of our protest came over to me because they had wanted some of our students to let the trucks come through.

470
01:12:10,000 --> 01:12:16,000
And the police refused to cross the line, but there were some company on trucks that wanted to come on into the plant.

471
01:12:16,000 --> 01:12:23,000
And some of the students had taken the part themselves to decide that they would continue to circle in the driveway and not let the trucks through.

472
01:12:23,000 --> 01:12:29,000
And so the police in charge came over to me and he said, look, I don't like this some bitch anymore you do.

473
01:12:29,000 --> 01:12:34,000
But you can't continue to block this driveway.

474
01:12:34,000 --> 01:12:39,000
It was none union.

475
01:12:39,000 --> 01:12:41,000
But you're going to have to do something here.

476
01:12:41,000 --> 01:12:52,000
And so I spoke to the kids and I told them I said, look, they said you're going to have to stop and let these trucks in.

477
01:12:52,000 --> 01:12:53,000
Oh, you're going to be arrested now.

478
01:12:53,000 --> 01:12:54,000
I'll leave it up to you all.

479
01:12:54,000 --> 01:13:00,000
Even though I was there as part of them, but I was addressing them as positive policemen.

480
01:13:00,000 --> 01:13:02,000
And I said, now if you stay, I'll join you.

481
01:13:02,000 --> 01:13:07,000
But if you want to leave, then now is the time to let these trucks through.

482
01:13:07,000 --> 01:13:23,000
And by this time, one of the priests, there was one of our supporters in a bean and pleaded with us yet again to let the trucks through Father Bernard Gilgun, Father Bernard Gilgun, who was an activist priest and wister.

483
01:13:23,000 --> 01:13:27,000
And so we then relented and that the trucks come through.

484
01:13:27,000 --> 01:13:36,000
But I'm saying that started was at least not just for the reasons of our civil rights protest, but because of the union issue.

485
01:13:36,000 --> 01:13:41,000
There were also some people that were supportive of what we were doing.

486
01:13:41,000 --> 01:13:54,000
But the opposition in the northeast was much more refined.

487
01:13:54,000 --> 01:14:02,000
The Wuster Area Council of Churches invited started to speak at a luncheon at their meeting.

488
01:14:02,000 --> 01:14:08,000
And we contacted them and said, well, let us come and give us that.

489
01:14:08,000 --> 01:14:11,000
This was in the wake of our picket and the plant.

490
01:14:11,000 --> 01:14:13,000
And they refused.

491
01:14:13,000 --> 01:14:19,000
And so we picketed the Wister Area Council of Churches, luncheon.

492
01:14:19,000 --> 01:14:26,000
And so it was really the quiet opposition that you had to deal with.

493
01:14:26,000 --> 01:14:32,000
We didn't have people threatening us on the sidewalks.

494
01:14:32,000 --> 01:14:47,000
One of the black ministers who was ahead at NACP and Wister Rubenstringfield criticized us picketing and said that we were going off half cocked when we picketed first the downtown department store.

495
01:14:47,000 --> 01:14:58,000
And so what we did was a number of us increased the membership of the NA with young people, students, from the campus and some people in black community.

496
01:14:58,000 --> 01:15:06,000
Then I called Rubenstringfield to the side and I said, look, we're going to picket the plant.

497
01:15:06,000 --> 01:15:10,000
And I want you to join us on the picket line.

498
01:15:10,000 --> 01:15:21,000
And I said, in essence, if you don't, we're going to move to vote you out at the end of the ACP.

499
01:15:21,000 --> 01:15:26,000
And so he resigned and we had an organization.

500
01:15:26,000 --> 01:15:36,000
But the result was that we were moving to preempt an attack from the NAACP, which we'd seen happen in our first picket.

501
01:15:36,000 --> 01:15:51,000
And so again, it was a matter of using strategy and from without going within the NAACP to boost the membership and therefore give ourselves a position of strength.

502
01:15:51,000 --> 01:16:04,000
Now when I was in Wister, now when I brought Malcolm X to speak, I had called Malcolm at his home in New York and asked if he would come and speak on the campus, which he agreed to do.

503
01:16:04,000 --> 01:16:13,000
And then a couple of the members of the board of our organization, White Minister said they would quit the organization unless we got someone to give the other point of view.

504
01:16:13,000 --> 01:16:22,000
And so when I told that back to Malcolm by phone and I had gotten him on the phone at his home, it was amazing that I was able to do it.

505
01:16:22,000 --> 01:16:30,000
But I did and I told him that they said that I'd have to have someone present to have the point of view and he said, well, I'll debate Talk to King.

506
01:16:30,000 --> 01:16:43,000
And so I said, well, all right, let me see what I can do. I called Atlanta and asked him if Dr. King would debate Malcolm and they said, no, he's not available, but the buy at Westernwood.

507
01:16:43,000 --> 01:16:52,000
And so when I talked back to Malcolm, he sort of chuckled on the phone and he said he knew that King wouldn't debate him, but he wasn't going to debate by Western.

508
01:16:52,000 --> 01:17:03,000
And so with that, I decided that if those ministers were going to quit, they were just going to have to quit because we were just going to go ahead and bring Malcolm to speak in Western, which we did.

509
01:17:03,000 --> 01:17:06,000
Did he say why he didn't want to debate Western?

510
01:17:06,000 --> 01:17:16,000
He thought Western was just a lackey for a front for King. He wanted to debate into King.

511
01:17:16,000 --> 01:17:28,000
So that was the debate he wanted. He wasn't going to debate some second. I mean, Western wasn't true. I mean, he's credited with being the leading star behind the scenes of the marginal life done.

512
01:17:28,000 --> 01:17:32,000
But that would have been a heck of a debate too, I think.

513
01:17:32,000 --> 01:17:37,000
In what? But Malcolm was going to have no part of that.

514
01:17:37,000 --> 01:17:57,000
So he came and I spent the day with him and he was just an extraordinary person. I went with him to the radio station, the front interview, started some station because of WTAG, but Julie Chase Fuller, who was one of the disc talkies there, conducted the interview.

515
01:17:57,000 --> 01:18:08,000
She was very supportive of what we were doing in the Worcester. She and I and Malcolm were at the interview together. I did mostly listening.

516
01:18:08,000 --> 01:18:23,000
It was mostly between her and Malcolm. There were a couple of times during the interview when I was kind of asked whether I agreed with Malcolm and I was careful not to get drawn into a May versus Malcolm X debate.

517
01:18:23,000 --> 01:18:32,000
Because I tended to agree with a lot of what Malcolm was saying. Now, of course, Malcolm, as you know, was not in favor of nonviolence and he made that very clear.

518
01:18:32,000 --> 01:18:43,000
But I was never an advocate of nonviolence as a belief, as I said earlier. We were forced into nonviolence by the reality of the circumstances.

519
01:18:43,000 --> 01:18:59,000
When I went from New Orleans to Bolulusa, with these two priests in the summer, let's say I was working in that summer in New Orleans and we went over and that would have been in the summer of 65.

520
01:18:59,000 --> 01:19:11,000
We were going to participate in a protest in Bolulusa. We got met on the other end of the Lake Puncher Train Bridge by armed colload of people with the Deacon's Foot of Fence and Justice.

521
01:19:11,000 --> 01:19:23,000
They followed us in the town, put us up in a house where they kept watch. Then at the rally, the march that we went to, they had people carrying shotguns alongside the march.

522
01:19:23,000 --> 01:19:34,000
And that didn't bother me in the least bit. I was rather reassured because the Deacon's philosophy was that we were going to fight back.

523
01:19:34,000 --> 01:19:48,000
In fact, and I don't know how historically accurate this is, but there was some scuttle butt that some whites had run through the black community attempted to intimidate them with some gunfire and that the Deacon's had fired back and wounded someone.

524
01:19:48,000 --> 01:19:55,000
But that it had been downplayed because they did not want that publicly known.

525
01:19:55,000 --> 01:20:07,000
So to me, now the kind of violence that I would have been against, however, would have been random violence. I mean self-defense was one thing.

526
01:20:07,000 --> 01:20:16,000
But proactive violence, for example, with the weatherman and others were doing fireball guns and that kind of thing.

527
01:20:17,000 --> 01:20:33,000
I would not have necessarily hourly condemned it to those who believed so firmly in their cause that they chose to resort to that.

528
01:20:34,000 --> 01:20:57,000
But I would not have been a part of it. But I can accept that some people would feel so strongly of the need for change and that other means that fail, that they would have to make some, take some acts of violence.

529
01:20:58,000 --> 01:21:11,000
And particularly, and I think for black people in general, I did not think that was particularly effective and defensible strategy.

530
01:21:12,000 --> 01:21:20,000
Did you involved with the Hicks family? Did they need me to interview the Hicks family in both of us?

531
01:21:20,000 --> 01:21:28,000
Hicks, yes. I thought you said hooks. I said, okay, Hicks, yes. In fact, I think I met some of them then when I was over there.

532
01:21:28,000 --> 01:21:45,000
Well, also that same summer that I went over for that march, I had actually, I was, what I was doing was, I was in my second year of law school, I believe, between the first and second year.

533
01:21:45,000 --> 01:21:53,000
And I was working actually out of the office of Ernest "Dutch" Morial, who was practicing law at the time, along with AP to roll.

534
01:21:53,000 --> 01:21:55,000
Ernest, who, I'm sorry?

535
01:21:55,000 --> 01:21:56,000
Ernest "Dutch" Morial.

536
01:21:56,000 --> 01:21:57,000
Moriel.

537
01:21:57,000 --> 01:22:07,000
Yeah. And he was one of, again, one of the black lawyers doing some work. He'd given me office space in his office in New Orleans.

538
01:22:07,000 --> 01:22:17,000
He later became mayor of New Orleans. And his son is actually now the national head of the Urban League, Marc Morial.

539
01:22:17,000 --> 01:22:23,000
But the reason I was in New Orleans at summer is summer of 65.

540
01:22:23,000 --> 01:22:25,000
Would you mind just waiting until the phone?

541
01:22:25,000 --> 01:22:27,000
No. Answer.

542
01:22:27,000 --> 01:22:29,000
Okay. Great. Sorry about that.

543
01:22:29,000 --> 01:22:37,000
When I was in New Orleans in the summer of 65, I was in between my first and second year of law school.

544
01:22:37,000 --> 01:22:46,000
And the NA Legal Offence Fund office in New York had hired a half dozen or so law students, mostly blacks.

545
01:22:46,000 --> 01:22:52,000
And they sent one of us each to a Southern state. That was the year that Title VII had become effective.

546
01:22:52,000 --> 01:22:58,000
It had been passed in 64, but you could begin to file complaints in 65.

547
01:22:58,000 --> 01:23:06,000
And so the Legal Offence Fund sent us out to employees to file Title VII complaints.

548
01:23:06,000 --> 01:23:12,000
And so I had gone over to Boelusa, even prior to that first march.

549
01:23:12,000 --> 01:23:20,000
And I had gotten workers at the Crown Zellabog plant in Boelusa to file Title VII complaints.

550
01:23:20,000 --> 01:23:25,000
In fact, those were some of the first complaints and most effective complaints under Title VII.

551
01:23:25,000 --> 01:23:29,000
But that was the work that I was doing with the Legal Offence Fund that summer.

552
01:23:29,000 --> 01:23:31,000
Okay. All right.

553
01:23:31,000 --> 01:23:34,000
And then you finished law school at Yale?

554
01:23:34,000 --> 01:23:42,000
Yeah. At that time I had done a year's law study at Boston University.

555
01:23:42,000 --> 01:23:51,000
And while there I'd gotten involved with a group called Law Students Civil Rights Research Council, this week.

556
01:23:51,000 --> 01:23:58,000
And it had been formed by some Northeastern law students.

557
01:23:58,000 --> 01:24:08,000
It was founded by private foundations, New York, Fawn, the Taconic Foundation, Rockefeller Brothers Fund, New York foundations, some others.

558
01:24:08,000 --> 01:24:18,000
And the idea with the LSCRRC Law Student Civil Rights Research Council was that the lawyers in the South who were doing civil rights work was overwhelmed that they needed help.

559
01:24:18,000 --> 01:24:26,000
And the best way to help them was to take some of the top law students from universities around the country and send them to the South.

560
01:24:26,000 --> 01:24:34,000
And so we had funding to hire these law students in the summer and send them to all the South.

561
01:24:34,000 --> 01:24:45,000
We would hire about anywhere from 200 to 200 law students, pay them 30 dollars a week, which was just enough for them to pay for their food and laundry.

562
01:24:45,000 --> 01:24:47,000
And we'd put them out in a black community.

563
01:24:47,000 --> 01:24:49,000
And they would stay with people in the community.

564
01:24:49,000 --> 01:24:54,000
And the lawyers would typically help find a place for them to stay while they were assigned to the lawyers' offices.

565
01:24:54,000 --> 01:24:56,000
And they'd work there.

566
01:24:56,000 --> 01:25:00,000
It was a twofold strategy with LSCRRC.

567
01:25:00,000 --> 01:25:06,000
The first part of it was to provide this much needed help to these lawyers.

568
01:25:06,000 --> 01:25:10,000
We didn't confine ourselves to the South, but I'd say 90% of our students were in the South.

569
01:25:10,000 --> 01:25:17,000
But we also put lawyers in simple limitedties offices outside of the South to work with ACLU people.

570
01:25:17,000 --> 01:25:22,000
In fact, the headquarters for the organization was in the National Office of the ACLU.

571
01:25:22,000 --> 01:25:24,000
Oh, it was, okay.

572
01:25:24,000 --> 01:25:33,000
And so my first year of law study at Boston University, I organized a chapter of this organization at Boston University.

573
01:25:33,000 --> 01:25:40,000
And so that summer was when I did the work with Legal Defense Fund.

574
01:25:40,000 --> 01:25:43,000
Was that an assignment from this organization?

575
01:25:43,000 --> 01:25:44,000
No, it was separate.

576
01:25:44,000 --> 01:25:45,000
It was separate.

577
01:25:46,000 --> 01:25:51,000
And then I got accepted into Yale as a transfer student.

578
01:25:51,000 --> 01:25:57,000
And so instead of returning to BU, I went to New Haven.

579
01:25:57,000 --> 01:26:03,000
I actually had applied while I was at clock to Yale in Columbia and Hobbit and several other schools

580
01:26:03,000 --> 01:26:05,000
and had been rejected by all of them.

581
01:26:05,000 --> 01:26:07,000
I'd been accepted at Boston University.

582
01:26:07,000 --> 01:26:14,000
I was on my way back to a clock one day with one of my schoolmates back home.

583
01:26:14,000 --> 01:26:17,000
And I asked him to stop at Yale and we stopped over on the campus.

584
01:26:17,000 --> 01:26:20,000
And I went to the Dean of Admissions Office.

585
01:26:20,000 --> 01:26:25,000
And it turned out to be a one-on-white man, of course, all of the top people there are white.

586
01:26:25,000 --> 01:26:29,000
From ball of attenuation about 80 miles up the road from Memphis.

587
01:26:29,000 --> 01:26:35,000
And Dean Tate, Jack B. Tate, and we got to talking and he took a like and to men.

588
01:26:35,000 --> 01:26:38,000
We talked a little bit about my civil rights background.

589
01:26:38,000 --> 01:26:42,000
And he said, well, let me see if there's someone around still that I can introduce you to.

590
01:26:42,000 --> 01:26:45,000
None of the people keep people on the campus at the time.

591
01:26:45,000 --> 01:26:48,000
So he said, well, you go on back and let me see what I can do.

592
01:26:48,000 --> 01:26:53,000
So the end result was he got me on a waiting list, but they never had the openings.

593
01:26:53,000 --> 01:26:56,000
And so he said, you go on the New Year first year and then get in touch with me.

594
01:26:56,000 --> 01:27:00,000
And so it was that summer while I was working out of Murray Hill's office

595
01:27:00,000 --> 01:27:03,000
that Dean Tate sent me all that in and said, I could come to Yale as a transfer.

596
01:27:03,000 --> 01:27:07,000
So if you hadn't just stopped over on the campus, I never would have.

597
01:27:07,000 --> 01:27:08,000
That would have happened.

598
01:27:08,000 --> 01:27:09,000
That's amazing.

599
01:27:09,000 --> 01:27:10,000
That already been rejected.

600
01:27:10,000 --> 01:27:13,000
That's a great story.

601
01:27:13,000 --> 01:27:22,000
Okay. So just I guess continuing with the chronology that you after you graduate from

602
01:27:22,000 --> 01:27:24,000
well school at Yale.

603
01:27:24,000 --> 01:27:33,000
And following law school, I was the second summer after I had done that summer in New Orleans.

604
01:27:33,000 --> 01:27:40,000
I worked out of New York traveling around the South to coordinate these law students.

605
01:27:40,000 --> 01:27:47,000
And so I had developed a pretty good friendship with many of the leaders on different campuses.

606
01:27:47,000 --> 01:27:51,000
And we had campuses from California to New York.

607
01:27:51,000 --> 01:27:59,000
And there were about 35 law schools, I remember the chapters of LSCRRC.

608
01:28:00,000 --> 01:28:02,000
And so I was elected to National Director.

609
01:28:02,000 --> 01:28:07,000
The National Director would serve for each year they pick a new National Director.

610
01:28:07,000 --> 01:28:10,000
And that would be someone who would just finish law school.

611
01:28:10,000 --> 01:28:19,000
And so I went from law school to the headquarters, which was, as I say, in the National Office of the ACLU.

612
01:28:19,000 --> 01:28:21,000
In New York.

613
01:28:21,000 --> 01:28:24,000
And so that's what I did in my first year at a law school.

614
01:28:24,000 --> 01:28:35,000
And interestingly, Bill Robinson, who was the director before me, had gotten a deferment.

615
01:28:35,000 --> 01:28:40,000
Because by this time the draft was very alive and active.

616
01:28:40,000 --> 01:28:46,000
And I was prime candidate in terms of my age and being single.

617
01:28:46,000 --> 01:28:47,000
And we drafted.

618
01:28:47,000 --> 01:28:52,000
That had nothing to do quite honestly with the work that I was doing with LSCRRC.

619
01:28:52,000 --> 01:28:57,000
But Robinson had gotten the draft deferment working with the organization.

620
01:28:57,000 --> 01:29:02,000
And so I applied for a deferment as well when I went to work with LSCRRC.

621
01:29:02,000 --> 01:29:08,000
And I had letters from Jack Pemberton.

622
01:29:08,000 --> 01:29:12,000
And I think Robert L. Carter even, I just sent a letter for me.

623
01:29:12,000 --> 01:29:20,000
I had had some key national, civil rights people to write letters saying that this work that I was doing was in the National interest.

624
01:29:20,000 --> 01:29:24,000
So I came down to Memphis and I met with a draft board.

625
01:29:24,000 --> 01:29:26,000
We had one black on the draft board.

626
01:29:26,000 --> 01:29:28,000
My brother had talked with him.

627
01:29:28,000 --> 01:29:30,000
And he was very supportive.

628
01:29:30,000 --> 01:29:32,000
And I was thinking about four whites on the board.

629
01:29:32,000 --> 01:29:33,000
And I came down and talked with him.

630
01:29:33,000 --> 01:29:40,000
Well, one of the white ladies, when I got into the meeting with him, she was intrigued to know what I was,

631
01:29:40,000 --> 01:29:41,000
what kind of work I was doing.

632
01:29:41,000 --> 01:29:43,000
And we got to talk about civil rights.

633
01:29:43,000 --> 01:29:49,000
Well, it turns out she had had a daughter who had been somewhat involved in civil rights activities in the North.

634
01:29:49,000 --> 01:29:57,000
But the long story that story was that after a very cordial meeting, they gave me a deferment.

635
01:29:57,000 --> 01:30:07,000
And this was in 1967 from a draft board here in Memphis that said that my work as a director in New York was in the National interest.

636
01:30:07,000 --> 01:30:10,000
And therefore, they granted me a deferment.

637
01:30:10,000 --> 01:30:18,000
And so, of course, that year's deferment actually got me past the age limit where I would have been drafted.

638
01:30:18,000 --> 01:30:29,000
Because I was kind of torn really personally because if I had gotten drafted, I didn't quite know what I would have done.

639
01:30:29,000 --> 01:30:36,000
I was pretty strong in my belief that the war was wrong.

640
01:30:36,000 --> 01:30:47,000
And I don't think that I was prepared to put my life on the line and go to Vietnam on a war that I felt was wrong.

641
01:30:47,000 --> 01:30:57,000
So, but I never had to come to really make those tough choices because I got the deferment.

642
01:30:57,000 --> 01:31:05,000
But I think that I would have rather gone to jail than to have gone to Vietnam war.

643
01:31:05,000 --> 01:31:08,000
Of course, this was 1967.

644
01:31:08,000 --> 01:31:16,000
The height I would have been going to teach ends in Boston, starting Howard Zinn and others were speaking at these.

645
01:31:16,000 --> 01:31:25,000
And making some very persuasive presentations about the wrong of the war.

646
01:31:25,000 --> 01:31:28,000
And I was convinced that it was wrong.

647
01:31:28,000 --> 01:31:33,000
And so, I was, Norman Thomas was one of the people that I brought to speak at the Clark campus as well.

648
01:31:33,000 --> 01:31:34,000
I was still in Worcester.

649
01:31:34,000 --> 01:31:43,000
So, anyway, I did the work there with the LSCRRC for that year.

650
01:31:43,000 --> 01:31:55,000
In fact, I raised a special grant money and sent ten law students down here to work with the Lawyers doing a sanitation strike when they were on strike.

651
01:31:55,000 --> 01:31:59,000
And the first suspect, Alex Hurder, I think, was his name.

652
01:31:59,000 --> 01:32:02,000
He is now a law professor in Vanderbilt.

653
01:32:02,000 --> 01:32:05,000
Alex Hurder, I think, is Herder.

654
01:32:05,000 --> 01:32:16,000
But he was the first person taken into custody in Memphis as a suspect in the assassination because he was a white person down around the Lorraine Motel Motel at the time of the assassination.

655
01:32:16,000 --> 01:32:22,000
Of course, he was released relatively soon afterwards.

656
01:32:22,000 --> 01:32:30,000
But the night of the assassination, I was in my office.

657
01:32:30,000 --> 01:32:38,000
I basically closed down. This was about six o'clock New Yorktown, which was closer to seven here.

658
01:32:38,000 --> 01:32:42,000
And my secretary came out and told me that the radio had announced.

659
01:32:42,000 --> 01:32:44,000
And she'd heard on the radio, Dr. King had been shot.

660
01:32:44,000 --> 01:32:48,000
And then a minute later, she came back out and said that he was dead.

661
01:32:48,000 --> 01:33:02,000
And what I was working late that night because I was getting my... I had a flight to Memphis schedule for the next day because there was going to be a march that Dr. King was to lead within three or four days.

662
01:33:02,000 --> 01:33:04,000
I think April the 8th.

663
01:33:04,000 --> 01:33:14,000
So of course, New York was tense and on the edge that night.

664
01:33:14,000 --> 01:33:18,000
And I did take a plane the next day and come to Memphis.

665
01:33:18,000 --> 01:33:24,000
And then I went on from Memphis to Atlanta where they had his funeral services, but I couldn't get into him.

666
01:33:24,000 --> 01:33:26,000
And I didn't even need him because it was packed so I stood up.

667
01:33:26,000 --> 01:33:34,000
I hadn't been went over to the Morehouse campus where they had a caravan from the church.

668
01:33:34,000 --> 01:33:38,000
And I think they brought his body over there and they had speakers and things at the Morehouse campus.

669
01:33:38,000 --> 01:33:50,000
Well, but following my work with the Law Students Council in New York, which ended in 68, then I had to decide...

670
01:33:50,000 --> 01:33:58,000
I had office to stay in New York and work either at NYU Law School or with some foundations.

671
01:33:58,000 --> 01:34:04,000
And I had an offer to go out to work with Cummins Engine Foundation.

672
01:34:04,000 --> 01:34:10,000
Philip Sorensen and had made me...

673
01:34:10,000 --> 01:34:14,000
and offered me a position with the foundation out there.

674
01:34:14,000 --> 01:34:21,000
But I had been out to California because we had chapters at UC Hastings College of the Law and at Boalt Hall and at UCLA.

675
01:34:21,000 --> 01:34:32,000
When I was in the Bay Area there, visiting the chapters during that year that I was running the organization, I had a great time and it was such a beautiful area.

676
01:34:32,000 --> 01:34:42,000
And one of the former presidents or directors of my group was then working with legal services in San Francisco, Steve Antler.

677
01:34:42,000 --> 01:34:49,000
And so he persuaded the director out there to offer me a job on the staff of legal services in San Francisco.

678
01:34:49,000 --> 01:34:51,000
What's the last name, Steve?

679
01:34:51,000 --> 01:34:54,000
Antler, ATL and TLER.

680
01:34:54,000 --> 01:35:04,000
And so I chose to move out to San Francisco in the winter of 68.

681
01:35:04,000 --> 01:35:11,000
I actually took a two months and went to Europe by myself with a book called,

682
01:35:11,000 --> 01:35:14,000
You Up on 5 Dolls a Day.

683
01:35:14,000 --> 01:35:17,000
Remember that?

684
01:35:17,000 --> 01:35:19,000
It worked sometimes.

685
01:35:19,000 --> 01:35:32,000
I, on two or three occasions, was lucky enough to meet somebody who would take me in and that kind of helped me part of the way that while I was staying around over in Europe.

686
01:35:32,000 --> 01:35:40,000
But then I came out to California and that was about October and November of 68.

687
01:35:40,000 --> 01:35:47,000
I started practicing law in San Francisco and continued to do that with legal services.

688
01:35:47,000 --> 01:35:55,000
I was in the Central Office doing test case litigation, primarily on areas of consumer fraud.

689
01:35:55,000 --> 01:36:04,000
And I became outspoken among the, we had Central Office and then there were neighborhood offices, two of which were run by black lawyers.

690
01:36:04,000 --> 01:36:18,000
And you know, you have to always leave your own motives up for examination whether by others or by yourself.

691
01:36:18,000 --> 01:36:30,000
And when I had taken that job, I thought that I had kind of reached an understanding with the director that I'd be able to do some other things.

692
01:36:30,000 --> 01:36:37,000
But I think that part of it is, I'm not well fit to work for people, I don't think, to be on a job.

693
01:36:37,000 --> 01:36:53,000
I mean, I started asking questions and I started challenging the authority of the leadership and talking about the fairness with which other employees were being treated in the Central Office and then the neighborhoods.

694
01:36:53,000 --> 01:37:13,000
And it led to some polarization within the offices, particularly in the Central Office, to the point that I went to the board meeting and said that the director ought to be lying, which he did.

695
01:37:13,000 --> 01:37:20,000
And he said that they had a black guy that came in and he fired me within.

696
01:37:20,000 --> 01:37:25,000
Very short time after.

697
01:37:25,000 --> 01:37:36,000
And I filed a lawsuit on the lawyers, white lawyer on the staff who was one of my supporters filed a suit for me in federal court.

698
01:38:06,000 --> 01:38:14,000
I didn't think including the lawyers would be treated with the same degree of fairness that others were.

699
01:38:14,000 --> 01:38:22,000
And they agreed, I mean, the ethnic and black lawyers agreed with me, but they as often happens, people don't speak up.

700
01:38:22,000 --> 01:38:28,000
They support you and they'll tell you quietly how much they agree with you.

701
01:38:28,000 --> 01:38:31,000
But you get left out there on that lamb, you know.

702
01:38:31,000 --> 01:38:34,000
You want to go battle with you.

703
01:38:34,000 --> 01:38:36,000
And of course, that's part of it.

704
01:38:36,000 --> 01:38:43,000
If you and I were willing to be on that limb by yourself, then you better stay at home because that's going to happen time and again.

705
01:38:43,000 --> 01:38:47,000
So you found yourself on that limb a few times in your life?

706
01:38:47,000 --> 01:38:57,000
But I've been blessed that when I fall on the limb, there's always another net somewhere.

707
01:38:57,000 --> 01:39:00,000
And another one.

708
01:39:00,000 --> 01:39:02,000
It's a compliment.

709
01:39:02,000 --> 01:39:16,000
Because while I was with legal services in San Francisco, a young white fellow came to me and volunteered and confessed to his wife had a lot of money.

710
01:39:16,000 --> 01:39:20,000
And he didn't know what to do with it. He felt guilty about it.

711
01:39:20,000 --> 01:39:29,000
And after he turned down my initial suggestion that they could give me a million dollars, which I actually didn't tell him.

712
01:39:29,000 --> 01:39:32,000
And he looked at me seriously and said, well, he would think about it.

713
01:39:32,000 --> 01:39:34,000
And he went and talked with his life about it.

714
01:39:34,000 --> 01:39:41,000
And the reason I said that was because you can't make change without money.

715
01:39:41,000 --> 01:39:46,000
I mean, whether it's in civil rights or any other kind of struggle, it takes money. It took money in the movement.

716
01:39:46,000 --> 01:39:48,000
It took money with our lost students.

717
01:39:48,000 --> 01:39:56,000
I was going to mention this when you talked about the foundations that supported your lost student organization.

718
01:39:56,000 --> 01:40:08,000
Because to me, that is one of the great untold stories of the civil rights movement at that time was the Rockefeller Foundation support, the conic, the movement couldn't have survived without those.

719
01:40:08,000 --> 01:40:14,000
And when those foundations did disappear or stopped giving money, it really changed the world.

720
01:40:14,000 --> 01:40:23,000
Absolutely. And what happened was that Congress saw the impact that these foundations was having.

721
01:40:23,000 --> 01:40:27,000
And they then attacked these foundations and intimidated them one after another.

722
01:40:27,000 --> 01:40:31,000
And backed them off.

723
01:40:31,000 --> 01:40:39,000
Because I mean, one of the, I mean, Leslie W. Dunbar, who let the field foundation.

724
01:40:39,000 --> 01:40:48,000
You know, he was one of the, I mean, Marian Wright Edelman, he got Marian Wright Edelman to start it and build in the Children's Defense Fund.

725
01:40:48,000 --> 01:40:59,000
He was close to, he got John Lewis. In fact, it came to the, when Vernon E. Jordan Jr had hit it, the Voter Education Project in Atlanta for the Southern Regional Council.

726
01:40:59,000 --> 01:41:08,000
When Vernon left that, it came down to whether they were going to have me or John Lewis.

727
01:41:08,000 --> 01:41:20,000
When I said they, Leslie W. Dunbar was really the person who was talking to both of us about taking that position as the head of the Voter Education Project, Voter Education Project.

728
01:41:20,000 --> 01:41:33,000
And Leslie, he said, well, look, he said, John can use this position at this time much more than the news.

729
01:41:33,000 --> 01:41:41,000
In essence, what he is, how he kind of made the decision. It was two good men that he had to do it. And he picked John.

730
01:41:41,000 --> 01:41:50,000
But when I was in San Francisco, I was, he hired me as a consultant to the field foundations.

731
01:41:50,000 --> 01:41:57,000
So I would go back and meet with the board, which was chaired by Ruth Field.

732
01:41:57,000 --> 01:42:03,000
But if you want it, I organized while I was on the City Council in Berkeley, California.

733
01:42:03,000 --> 01:42:09,000
And two black kids got killed on the campus of Southern in a protest demonstration.

734
01:42:09,000 --> 01:42:13,000
And that was, I think, around 1972, everyone's 72.

735
01:42:13,000 --> 01:42:22,000
And the media was unclear about how they got killed or who killed them, or they'd been killed by Sheriff's Deputy on the campus.

736
01:42:22,000 --> 01:42:28,000
And then a lion of sheriff's deputy started firing at the students and two of them ended up dead.

737
01:42:28,000 --> 01:42:31,000
And they said, they never knew who did it.

738
01:42:31,000 --> 01:42:36,000
And so I called black lawyer that I knew in Baton Rouge. He said, well, you could help if you came down.

739
01:42:36,000 --> 01:42:42,000
And I called Les Dunbar in New York. And I said, Les, I said, I'd like to go down to Baton Rouge.

740
01:42:42,000 --> 01:42:48,000
And so he said, well, all right. So he gave me $5,000 of money from Field Foundation.

741
01:42:48,000 --> 01:42:56,000
And he contacted John Lewis and Owusu Sadaukai, who was the leader of a black nationalist group.

742
01:42:56,000 --> 01:43:01,000
And my brother out of Memphis took another black councilman with me from Berkeley, California.

743
01:43:01,000 --> 01:43:05,000
And we, W. Haywood Burns, who was head in the National Conference of Black Lawyers.

744
01:43:05,000 --> 01:43:12,000
And we went down to Baton Rouge and convened what we call the black people's community inquiry into the shooting depths of these students.

745
01:43:12,000 --> 01:43:19,000
And we had hearings. And then actually the governor came to the hearing to come and have it.

746
01:43:19,000 --> 01:43:25,000
But we focused attention and got the story out. But I mentioned that because I would not have been able to do that.

747
01:43:25,000 --> 01:43:29,000
If I hadn't been able to pick up phone call Les Dunbar, I'd get that $5,000 from them.

748
01:43:29,000 --> 01:43:37,000
They would be ten. But because actually when I left California, he gave me $5,000 to help me relocate from California.

749
01:43:37,000 --> 01:43:39,000
So he was helping out individual.

750
01:43:39,000 --> 01:43:47,000
Yeah, I gave him a grant. He was to write a story on black lawyers in Tennessee.

751
01:43:47,000 --> 01:43:51,000
So that was, yeah, it's a way of getting it done, getting you some money, sure.

752
01:43:51,000 --> 01:44:05,000
But you see, if I went to him when I had a project, I could go to the Norman Foundation or the Vanguard Foundation that I think was a new world foundation,

753
01:44:05,000 --> 01:44:11,000
or I'd have been less than done by it field. But Lesley could talk to the heads of the other foundations.

754
01:44:11,000 --> 01:44:14,000
And then they would act as a consortium to put the money together to find it.

755
01:44:14,000 --> 01:44:18,000
What was the first thing you said in the new world?

756
01:44:18,000 --> 01:44:21,000
Debbie was with the Norman Foundation.

757
01:44:21,000 --> 01:44:29,000
Norman Foundation. And there was Taconic Foundation. There was Rockefeller Brothers Fund. There was the New York Foundation.

758
01:44:29,000 --> 01:44:37,000
Cummins Engine Foundation out of Indiana. Stern Family Fund out of New Orleans.

759
01:44:37,000 --> 01:44:41,000
So these were all well known to people in the movement where they could get the money?

760
01:44:41,000 --> 01:44:42,000
Absolutely.

761
01:44:42,000 --> 01:44:43,000
Where money could be.

762
01:44:43,000 --> 01:44:44,000
Exactly.

763
01:44:44,000 --> 01:44:46,000
And it was the same group. Same group with foundations.

764
01:44:46,000 --> 01:44:54,000
And without them, you know, much of this wouldn't have happened.

765
01:44:54,000 --> 01:44:58,000
And they had the kind of relationship with leaders, including King and others.

766
01:44:58,000 --> 01:45:08,000
Cesar Chavez, done by helped the United Farm Workers through the support that he could generate.

767
01:45:08,000 --> 01:45:13,000
So, yes, these...

768
01:45:13,000 --> 01:45:22,000
So my friends in San Francisco, they were...it was ironic because when my friend came to me and he said...

769
01:45:22,000 --> 01:45:25,000
He said, you know...

770
01:45:25,000 --> 01:45:29,000
You want me to stop for a second?

771
01:45:29,000 --> 01:45:36,000
My friend came to me and said, you know, I told you earlier that I had some money, but it actually was quite a lot of money.

772
01:45:36,000 --> 01:45:45,000
And we...I'd like your ideas what do it. And I said, well, give me a million dollars. The reason I said that was because...

773
01:45:45,000 --> 01:45:52,000
I knew that my commitment would be to use that money to stir up things, to make things happen, to change things.

774
01:45:52,000 --> 01:45:58,000
It wasn't just to go live constantly on a boat somewhere. But I would be free of strings if it was my money.

775
01:45:58,000 --> 01:46:07,000
So he came back and said, well, we're not going to do that, but what we will do is we'll bring a million dollars from the Northeast out here to California,

776
01:46:07,000 --> 01:46:11,000
and set up a trust and put you in charge of it. And then you can take the money.

777
01:46:11,000 --> 01:46:22,000
He said that you can take all of the interest or dividends and earnings because they put it into an account at Bank of America,

778
01:46:22,000 --> 01:46:28,000
which was in turn invested. And so you can take the dividend money and give it away heavy-wish.

779
01:46:28,000 --> 01:46:33,000
And plus you can go into the corpus at least to a hundred thousand dollars without talking to us.

780
01:46:33,000 --> 01:46:37,000
And they paid me ten thousand dollars salary to do this.

781
01:46:37,000 --> 01:46:47,000
Now the purpose for them doing this, saying it up, was they said, we want you to give this money to projects that are not tax exempt,

782
01:46:47,000 --> 01:46:53,000
that the ones that are now getting support from foundations and alike, those are not the ones we want to support.

783
01:46:53,000 --> 01:46:58,000
We want to give it to non-taxative exempt organizations.

784
01:46:58,000 --> 01:47:03,000
And so I was able to pick and choose different projects going on around the country.

785
01:47:03,000 --> 01:47:16,000
And I did that. Of course, that was just a part-time position, but I also, as I said, was engaged as a consultant to field foundation at the same time.

786
01:47:16,000 --> 01:47:25,000
And was a consultant with another group that was recruiting minority law students, Cleo, Councilor Legal Education,

787
01:47:25,000 --> 01:47:30,000
and then I was recruiting Blackshin, I think I was name it.

788
01:47:30,000 --> 01:47:49,000
Anyway, so with the funds, so after I had gotten fired at Legal Services, I was able to continue to float with the independent income I had coming in.

789
01:47:49,000 --> 01:47:52,000
Well, I was living in Berkeley, California because...

790
01:47:52,000 --> 01:47:55,000
I was a foundation ever, I have a name, or was that quiet?

791
01:47:55,000 --> 01:47:59,000
Yes, we named it Bread Limited Trust.

792
01:47:59,000 --> 01:48:04,000
Bread Limited Trust. Meaning we didn't have a whole lot of money.

793
01:48:04,000 --> 01:48:06,000
I love it.

794
01:48:06,000 --> 01:48:09,000
All right.

795
01:48:09,000 --> 01:48:21,000
And so I was at the same time on the board of Berkeley, California Legal Services. In fact, at one point I became chairman of the board of Berkeley, California Legal Services.

796
01:48:21,000 --> 01:48:25,000
And I became active in the Berkeley, California Black Caucus.

797
01:48:25,000 --> 01:48:34,000
And so by the time Ron Dellums ran, he had been on the City Council and was very visible as a councilman out there.

798
01:48:34,000 --> 01:48:47,000
And so because of Dellems' eloquent statements against war, he became very supported by the white left.

799
01:48:47,000 --> 01:48:53,000
And so that's how he got to be elected Congress from there.

800
01:48:53,000 --> 01:49:04,000
And so when Dellems got elected to the Congress, my friend Ira Simmons and I, who at Arrowwoods of Lawyer, that had come out West and was working up in Sacramento,

801
01:49:04,000 --> 01:49:11,000
and I had encouraged him to come to Berkeley, California and helped him to get a post with the Berkeley, California Legal Services because I was on the board there.

802
01:49:11,000 --> 01:49:14,000
Also a Black player.

803
01:49:15,000 --> 01:49:25,000
And so he and I were spending the evening just relaxing at his home and we said, well, we ought to run for the council.

804
01:49:25,000 --> 01:49:29,000
Because Dellems had gotten elected so there was a Vegas degree.

805
01:49:29,000 --> 01:49:35,000
And so we said, well, we'll run a ticket of the team, two of us.

806
01:49:35,000 --> 01:49:38,000
I didn't know anything about the politics in Berkeley, California.

807
01:49:38,000 --> 01:49:42,000
This was just looking at what do we do next kind of thing.

808
01:49:42,000 --> 01:49:58,000
And so it, but that choice, that decision we made came at the same time that the white left had been planning and organizing for a good while to run candidates in the Berkeley, California City elections.

809
01:49:58,000 --> 01:50:03,000
And they had formed their group called the April Coalition.

810
01:50:03,000 --> 01:50:22,000
And so the deal that they had set up was that the white left, the April Coalition would pick two candidates, two whites, and the Berkeley, California Black Caucus would pick two black candidates.

811
01:50:22,000 --> 01:50:28,000
And those candidates would run as a slate to be endorsed by Ron Dellums.

812
01:50:29,000 --> 01:50:36,000
And so by this time, Ira Simmons were regular attendees at the Berkeley, California Black Caucus meeting.

813
01:50:36,000 --> 01:50:45,000
I had even given $500 or so of my friend's money to help them get a headquarters.

814
01:50:45,000 --> 01:50:52,000
And so we were liked within the caucus and we announced that we were going to run for council.

815
01:50:52,000 --> 01:51:01,000
And so they kind of got the caucus upset because they already had in mind who they were going to put onto the ticket in these two seats.

816
01:51:01,000 --> 01:51:06,000
And so they kind of pleaded with Ira Simmons, not to run.

817
01:51:06,000 --> 01:51:09,000
And Dellems pleaded with us.

818
01:51:09,000 --> 01:51:15,000
And so when they saw that we were going to move forward, then the plea was, well, why don't one of you run?

819
01:51:15,000 --> 01:51:21,000
And I said, no, that's not going to work because I didn't want to, if I showed that I was willing to dump Aaron,

820
01:51:21,000 --> 01:51:28,000
because he didn't have the money, I had the money, then that was sort of weak in me at the beginning.

821
01:51:28,000 --> 01:51:33,000
And might create an adversary that I didn't want.

822
01:51:33,000 --> 01:51:36,000
So I said, no, we are, it's both of us or nothing.

823
01:51:36,000 --> 01:51:44,000
So in the end, we forced the caucus to accept us as their two candidates because they knew that I had the money and that I was going to run.

824
01:51:44,000 --> 01:51:48,000
I went to my friends and I said, look, I'm going to run for council.

825
01:51:48,000 --> 01:51:53,000
I need you to put up the money. I need to use your money is what I said.

826
01:51:53,000 --> 01:51:55,000
And they said, all right.

827
01:51:55,000 --> 01:52:08,000
And so that's how I got to be, the two of us got on to the ticket with Loni Hancock and Rick Brown, who was the student.

828
01:52:08,000 --> 01:52:13,000
And so the April coalition knew nothing about us.

829
01:52:13,000 --> 01:52:16,000
We had had no dealings with them.

830
01:52:16,000 --> 01:52:19,000
And I'm going to turn that off.

831
01:52:19,000 --> 01:52:22,000
Okay, it's going.

832
01:52:22,000 --> 01:52:30,000
Great. So just pick up where we had been talking about the formation of the April coalition.

833
01:52:30,000 --> 01:52:35,000
You and I are, are, are, are, are put on the ticket?

834
01:52:35,000 --> 01:52:45,000
Yes. And the thing about it was that this was my first foray into elected politics in Canada.

835
01:52:45,000 --> 01:52:48,000
I never really seen myself as writing for office.

836
01:52:48,000 --> 01:52:57,000
In fact, when I went to sign up as a candidate at City Hall, the City Court clerk asked me my voter registration and I wasn't registered.

837
01:52:57,000 --> 01:53:01,000
And so I had to go register before I could sign up as a candidate.

838
01:53:01,000 --> 01:53:06,000
I had not lived in Berkeley, California, but three months before the election election was April.

839
01:53:06,000 --> 01:53:14,000
I moved from Kensington, California, which was a suburb, adjacent to Berkeley, California, into Berkeley, California 90 days before the election in order to qualify.

840
01:53:14,000 --> 01:53:21,000
And so, and it never, to be quite candid, I'd never been to a council meeting, or even in the council chambers.

841
01:53:21,000 --> 01:53:24,000
But as I said, Ira Simmons had made the decision that we were going to run.

842
01:53:24,000 --> 01:53:29,000
We thought it would be a good form, which we've been there long enough to see the energy and the politics of the area.

843
01:53:29,000 --> 01:53:32,000
And so we thought we could introduce some new thought.

844
01:53:32,000 --> 01:53:40,000
And so, when I had my announcement, I made a statement.

845
01:53:40,000 --> 01:53:44,000
And I don't think that people were paying much attention because again, we were very new.

846
01:53:44,000 --> 01:53:49,000
But I said that my first priority is going to be to the interest of the black community.

847
01:53:49,000 --> 01:53:51,000
And that was pure Southern.

848
01:53:51,000 --> 01:54:01,000
That was that was Deami Bailey speaking from in the context of my experience and politics here in the South, where if you're a black politician, then you're...

849
01:54:01,000 --> 01:54:03,000
That was what you were about.

850
01:54:03,000 --> 01:54:06,000
You were about speaking for one advance interest of blacks.

851
01:54:06,000 --> 01:54:15,000
And so, I did not see that as being necessarily much different from what my agenda should and would be in Northern California.

852
01:54:15,000 --> 01:54:22,000
Because I knew that the interest of whites, I could look at the platform and the work that was being done.

853
01:54:22,000 --> 01:54:30,000
Well, also knew that we would look upon with suspicion about a black Indigenous black community there, because they were not that supportive of the white left.

854
01:54:30,000 --> 01:54:36,000
They always had questions about the motives and even though the Panthers were close with the white left.

855
01:54:36,000 --> 01:54:41,000
And there was support for the Panthers, but there was some suspicion or discomfort there too.

856
01:54:41,000 --> 01:54:43,000
So here we are in new commerce.

857
01:54:43,000 --> 01:54:47,000
And we had to establish our own sense of legitimacy first with a base.

858
01:54:47,000 --> 01:54:48,000
That would be the black community.

859
01:54:48,000 --> 01:54:52,000
And in fact, the April coalition wanted us to run a joint campaign office.

860
01:54:52,000 --> 01:54:55,000
I said, no, so we'll open our own office in the black community.

861
01:54:55,000 --> 01:55:01,000
And we're not going to start carrying your two candidates with us into the community to campaign.

862
01:55:01,000 --> 01:55:04,000
And so we've got not there and introduced ourselves.

863
01:55:04,000 --> 01:55:06,000
And then we'll bring you in.

864
01:55:06,000 --> 01:55:15,000
And so, early on in the campaign, we were offering some feathers in terms of the position we had already ruffled the feathers of the caucus.

865
01:55:15,000 --> 01:55:22,000
We had put delums in a fix in terms of having to endorse us.

866
01:55:22,000 --> 01:55:27,000
And one of the people that he wanted to run was his good friend, Ken Simmons, who was going to be one of the two.

867
01:55:27,000 --> 01:55:30,000
That was already supposed to fill those seats.

868
01:55:30,000 --> 01:55:39,000
And so by the time we won the election, and we had started working with the, bringing the white candidates into the black community.

869
01:55:40,000 --> 01:55:48,000
But by this time, we were pretty strong forces in our own right as politicians having to run a very strong campaign.

870
01:55:48,000 --> 01:55:53,000
And I brought in merely everyone who walked the streets of Berkeley, California with us to help us campaign.

871
01:55:53,000 --> 01:55:57,000
I had Julian Bond, who cut a radio spot for me.

872
01:55:57,000 --> 01:56:03,000
And we had a damn good campaign manager that we had.

873
01:56:03,000 --> 01:56:05,000
We had two initially that were not that good.

874
01:56:05,000 --> 01:56:12,000
And we ended up with one who knew what he was doing, Boulsettner, who had campaigned with Birch Bayh out in Indiana.

875
01:56:12,000 --> 01:56:15,000
He was a lost student of that time at Boulte.

876
01:56:15,000 --> 01:56:18,000
And so came election day, we were on a roll.

877
01:56:18,000 --> 01:56:20,000
We had some friction.

878
01:56:20,000 --> 01:56:27,000
There were points in which the coalition was about to fall apart because of our determination to set our own agenda.

879
01:56:27,000 --> 01:56:31,000
But we held together and then came election.

880
01:56:31,000 --> 01:56:36,000
And we had two of the three seats, Loni Hancock, who won the other one.

881
01:56:36,000 --> 01:56:39,000
And they're fourth kind of, they lost.

882
01:56:39,000 --> 01:56:45,000
And so we came in too strong to one strong on the white left, at least the far white left.

883
01:56:45,000 --> 01:56:51,000
Because Berkeley, California's left was not all homogeneous.

884
01:56:51,000 --> 01:56:57,000
I mean, one of my strongest supporters then, and throughout was Dan Siegel, who had been the president of the student body.

885
01:56:57,000 --> 01:57:03,000
And luckily, who sort of was speaking on the campus when he said, let's go down and retake the park.

886
01:57:03,000 --> 01:57:12,000
And that's what led to a deadly confrontation down until our pavingew about the demonstrations against people's park.

887
01:57:12,000 --> 01:57:15,000
So I had to support.

888
01:57:15,000 --> 01:57:19,000
And then I had some run-ins with the Panthers, but Huey Newton.

889
01:57:19,000 --> 01:57:22,000
Huey Newton the Panthers.

890
01:57:22,000 --> 01:57:25,000
Again, I'm not a joiner.

891
01:57:25,000 --> 01:57:30,000
I tried to make that as diplomatically clear to here as I could that I would support his programs.

892
01:57:30,000 --> 01:57:37,000
He said, you know, you come and put your office in hours, we'll feature you in our Black Panther newspaper.

893
01:57:37,000 --> 01:57:43,000
And I begged off from that, well, I would go to here his penthouse at 12, when you'd make sure to drive our,

894
01:57:43,000 --> 01:57:46,000
and I would meet with him and talk with him time to time.

895
01:57:46,000 --> 01:57:51,000
And I had some Chivas Regal and have an enjoyable visit.

896
01:57:51,000 --> 01:57:57,000
But he then asked me for money, asked me for $25,000, and I told him that I didn't have it.

897
01:57:57,000 --> 01:58:04,000
And from that point, he began to become threatening and I had to stop visiting with Huey.

898
01:58:04,000 --> 01:58:11,000
But I continued to support on the council the programs that the Panthers were pushing, the Free Breakfast Program.

899
01:58:11,000 --> 01:58:16,000
We found it some of their daycare programs and other things.

900
01:58:17,000 --> 01:58:23,000
The Conservatives who had initially said they were going to recall all three of us said then that, well,

901
01:58:23,000 --> 01:58:28,000
let's not recall a lighty handcock, she's not a big problem, that barely is the problem.

902
01:58:28,000 --> 01:58:33,000
But they wanted to get both me and Irish Simmons, my colleague.

903
01:58:33,000 --> 01:58:37,000
But then Wilmot Sweeney, who was a conservative Black Council member, the first Black Councilman,

904
01:58:37,000 --> 01:58:42,000
and Berkeley, California said, well, you can't do that if you're going to drop off the White Woman on here,

905
01:58:42,000 --> 01:58:46,000
then you can't just run a recall against two Blacks.

906
01:58:46,000 --> 01:58:49,000
And so at that point, they said, well, let's drop Irish Simmons.

907
01:58:49,000 --> 01:58:55,000
And so I was then the one they chose to focus in on because they had figured,

908
01:58:55,000 --> 01:59:01,000
and I think correctly so that if they could get me, then they succeeded in that,

909
01:59:01,000 --> 01:59:09,000
that they would be able to stop the force of what we were doing, which was using the council chamber

910
01:59:10,000 --> 01:59:14,000
as a megaphone to demand change and get change.

911
01:59:14,000 --> 01:59:16,000
Philibust in the meeting? Yes, I did.

912
01:59:16,000 --> 01:59:21,000
I would talk in the council meetings at some times to the point that the mayor, who was Black,

913
01:59:21,000 --> 01:59:23,000
which said, well, Mr. Bill, you out of order.

914
01:59:23,000 --> 01:59:27,000
And I would keep talking and he would ask the clerk to turn my microphone off,

915
01:59:27,000 --> 01:59:29,000
and I would stand and continue to talk.

916
01:59:29,000 --> 01:59:34,000
And of course, we had a crowd, typically the meetings were crowded with people.

917
01:59:34,000 --> 01:59:39,000
And we had issues that we were fighting, and I had a staff, because I had taken,

918
01:59:39,000 --> 01:59:47,000
not only when I found my campaign accounts showing that I'd spent $25,000 in the campaign,

919
01:59:47,000 --> 01:59:53,000
and I listed 25 as being anonymous, which you could do in California at the time.

920
01:59:53,000 --> 01:59:56,000
And that raised a lot of our roles, and where's the money coming from?

921
01:59:56,000 --> 02:00:00,000
So not only was I then being accused of being a COVID-bagger,

922
02:00:00,000 --> 02:00:03,000
because that was one of the things that conservative views against me.

923
02:00:03,000 --> 02:00:06,000
But then, of course, it wasn't, where's he getting this funding from?

924
02:00:06,000 --> 02:00:12,000
Well, the agreement that I had made with my friends was that I was not going to put their name out in public.

925
02:00:12,000 --> 02:00:17,000
I mean, they were two quiet people, young people, and they did not want the notoriety.

926
02:00:17,000 --> 02:00:24,000
In fact, Mike Wallace interviewed me on 60 minutes, and asked me, well, where's your money coming from?

927
02:00:24,000 --> 02:00:28,000
And I was a bit surprised, because he had been very charming.

928
02:00:28,000 --> 02:00:33,000
We met on the campus of UC Berkeley, California, and then we'd driven over to my,

929
02:00:33,000 --> 02:00:38,000
I had a little cottage right near the Berkeley, California Hills, and we sat out on the patio,

930
02:00:38,000 --> 02:00:42,000
and as soon as the camera started rolling, he became quite a different person.

931
02:00:42,000 --> 02:00:46,000
And went after me, and he wanted to know where was the money coming from,

932
02:00:46,000 --> 02:00:48,000
and I was a little surprised by that.

933
02:00:48,000 --> 02:00:50,000
And I said, well, I'm not going to tell you.

934
02:00:50,000 --> 02:00:54,000
So, what are you living up here in a nice place, and you're driving a nice car,

935
02:00:54,000 --> 02:00:55,000
and people have a right to know.

936
02:00:55,000 --> 02:01:00,000
I said, well, the less you know about me, the stronger I am, I'm not going to let people know everything about me.

937
02:01:00,000 --> 02:01:07,000
And I felt that way that, that if you know the source of my support, then you know where you can make your attack.

938
02:01:07,000 --> 02:01:12,000
And so I didn't tell him, well, this aired actually on 60 minutes, this segment.

939
02:01:12,000 --> 02:01:16,000
But before he aired it, he called me from New York, and he said,

940
02:01:16,000 --> 02:01:22,000
Deami, I'm putting this show together, and I'm going to give you one last opportunity to tell me where your money's coming from.

941
02:01:23,000 --> 02:01:25,000
And I said, well, I'm sorry, I'm not going to tell you.

942
02:01:25,000 --> 02:01:28,000
He said, well, if you don't tell us, we're going to find out anyway.

943
02:01:28,000 --> 02:01:33,000
And I said, well, you mean he said, well, there's a group that's put up some funds to find out where your money's coming from.

944
02:01:33,000 --> 02:01:43,000
So, I called Leslie W. Dunbar after that back in New York, and I said, less, I said, Mike Wallace tells me that somebody has put up money in fact, I wear my money's coming from him.

945
02:01:43,000 --> 02:01:46,000
And he said, well, let me look into it.

946
02:01:46,000 --> 02:01:53,000
And so he called me back, and he said, sure enough, there was a group called the Fund for Investigative Journalism,

947
02:01:53,000 --> 02:01:57,000
and that they had gotten a grant from the Stern family, I don't know all of this, too.

948
02:01:57,000 --> 02:01:59,000
And I wear my money's coming from him.

949
02:01:59,000 --> 02:02:10,000
Now, this continued to be a so-and-so point in Berkeley, California, and it was kind of dogged at my heels, because I wouldn't tell who this was.

950
02:02:11,000 --> 02:02:20,000
At one point, there was a counterintelligence black spy for the government, for California, who actually revealed himself as such.

951
02:02:20,000 --> 02:02:26,000
He would go into radical organization and stir up dissent and distrust, and he had infiltrated my campaign.

952
02:02:26,000 --> 02:02:30,000
And he wrote about it in a book, the Glass House tapes.

953
02:02:30,000 --> 02:02:39,000
But at one point, he went on radio in Los Angeles and said he had given me $10,000 to help him infiltrate the Angela Davis campaign.

954
02:02:39,000 --> 02:02:46,000
And I had to then go to KPFA, the sister station in Berkeley, California.

955
02:02:46,000 --> 02:02:51,000
And he was on the microphone in Los Angeles, where he was making this out of land discharge.

956
02:02:51,000 --> 02:02:55,000
And I told him, told the station there that you've been in Berskate this before you run it.

957
02:02:55,000 --> 02:02:58,000
Well, clearly what he was trying to do was smoke me out.

958
02:02:58,000 --> 02:03:03,000
He knew that I couldn't reveal my financial solicits, and he was trying to discredit me.

959
02:03:04,000 --> 02:03:09,000
The guy I thought was just a bomb drunk who was hanging around the campaign headquarters.

960
02:03:09,000 --> 02:03:12,000
But in truth, he actually was a spy.

961
02:03:12,000 --> 02:03:22,000
And fortunately for me, a reporter from the Mohamad Speaks of Black Muslim News, they became out from Chicago, an investigator story, and they did a good story.

962
02:03:22,000 --> 02:03:31,000
KPFA didn't air the charges, but I was in a rather tough pickle there for a few minutes, based upon this kind of activity.

963
02:03:31,000 --> 02:03:35,000
But again, that's the kind of thing that you had to live with and go.

964
02:03:35,000 --> 02:03:38,000
In the one time of my life was threatened.

965
02:03:38,000 --> 02:03:40,000
I had to have around the clock secured.

966
02:03:40,000 --> 02:03:44,000
So I just said they knew about a contract on my life.

967
02:03:44,000 --> 02:03:49,000
And it turned out it was an extortion plot, which someone wanted me to pay them some money.

968
02:03:49,000 --> 02:03:54,000
He was eventually arrested by the Perkley Police.

969
02:03:54,000 --> 02:04:00,000
But so there were a few dull moments in the period.

970
02:04:00,000 --> 02:04:02,000
But again, we got changed.

971
02:04:02,000 --> 02:04:03,000
That was one thing.

972
02:04:03,000 --> 02:04:05,000
We made things happen.

973
02:04:07,000 --> 02:04:09,000
Take a quick break for a second.

974
02:04:09,000 --> 02:04:12,000
Do you have your better to be safe than sorry?

975
02:04:16,000 --> 02:04:19,000
The first thing I said to my fiancee was you got to tell me if there's anything in my case.

976
02:04:19,000 --> 02:04:20,000
Yes, absolutely.

977
02:04:20,000 --> 02:04:27,000
That was a pretty adventurous time.

978
02:04:27,000 --> 02:04:30,000
So they got the signature on the petition.

979
02:04:30,000 --> 02:04:40,000
The way recall works is that if you get 25% of the people who voted in the last election to sign a petition, then you forced into an election.

980
02:04:40,000 --> 02:04:47,000
And so they had 18,000 people already that had voted in the election when we were defeated.

981
02:04:48,000 --> 02:04:54,000
And so all they needed to do was organize a campaign with the money from the business community and the conservatives.

982
02:04:54,000 --> 02:04:58,000
And put on the ballot the question, shall the Army be recalled?

983
02:04:58,000 --> 02:04:59,000
Yes or no?

984
02:04:59,000 --> 02:05:05,000
Well, in order to survive once they get those signatures, then you have to get a majority.

985
02:05:05,000 --> 02:05:15,000
So it's no longer the situation where I had won with a plurality, but I never had a majority because the conservatives were still in the majority in Perkley at that time.

986
02:05:15,000 --> 02:05:16,000
And they knew that.

987
02:05:16,000 --> 02:05:26,000
And so I knew that by the time they got those signatures, that it was that that batch answers have defeated the recall, will be rather slim.

988
02:05:26,000 --> 02:05:27,000
Right.

989
02:05:27,000 --> 02:05:33,000
But and I knew that for two and a half years that I was under the specter of that happening.

990
02:05:33,000 --> 02:05:36,000
And it sounds like they were because of the way they could do that.

991
02:05:36,000 --> 02:05:40,000
They were going to recall somebody from your from that ticket.

992
02:05:41,000 --> 02:05:56,000
And a friend of mine, Roger Nash Baldwin, well I knew him because in New York his nephew and I were good friends and he had introduced me to Roger and we had launched a couple of times.

993
02:05:56,000 --> 02:06:03,000
He came out to the Bay Area to visit during the recall and I picked him up and he said, just pull over to the side of the road.

994
02:06:03,000 --> 02:06:13,000
And he said, look, he said, I've been out here and people I had that the information I get is that you're not going to beat this recall unless you tell where your money is coming from.

995
02:06:13,000 --> 02:06:19,000
Because people just don't like that kind of not knowing that kind of thing.

996
02:06:19,000 --> 02:06:26,000
And so that was another factor that I'm sure was on the table.

997
02:06:27,000 --> 02:06:40,000
What had happened was that my friends had closed down the trust as more and more questions began to be asked about the money, especially after I had one and reported that anonymous contribution.

998
02:06:40,000 --> 02:06:49,000
So they had given me $100,000 which they paid to taxes on and I used that money to pay staff.

999
02:06:49,000 --> 02:07:01,000
So I had a staff of well actually as many as 13 people several of them were students so I could get them on work studies so I didn't have to pay them full salary.

1000
02:07:01,000 --> 02:07:08,000
Then I had one full time person assigned to me by the Joint Center for Political and Economic Studies back in Washington.

1001
02:07:08,000 --> 02:07:12,000
And so I put together this quite competent staff.

1002
02:07:13,000 --> 02:07:24,000
So whenever I went to the Council meetings I had these thick books of information because my staff would go out, they would research all of the agenda items, they talk with people in the community.

1003
02:07:24,000 --> 02:07:30,000
And there's nothing that brings about change more than information probably used.

1004
02:07:30,000 --> 02:07:33,000
And that's what I went in there armed with on the council.

1005
02:07:33,000 --> 02:07:38,000
And that helped me to make a difference as a council member.

1006
02:07:39,000 --> 02:07:45,000
But by the time of the recall I used up a great deal of that 100 grand.

1007
02:07:45,000 --> 02:07:50,000
And I had probably a third of that money left.

1008
02:07:52,000 --> 02:07:58,000
Probably not that much but I had to spend most of what I had left fighting the recall.

1009
02:07:58,000 --> 02:08:05,000
So by the time the recall was over of course they didn't know it in California but my money was pretty well out anyway.

1010
02:08:05,000 --> 02:08:09,000
And I knew that it was going to run out because I wasn't practicing law.

1011
02:08:09,000 --> 02:08:20,000
I did as I say have some stipends coming in but I don't think I was at that point still doing the consultant work because it was limited work with the Field Foundation.

1012
02:08:20,000 --> 02:08:26,000
So financially the jig was going to be up anyway.

1013
02:08:26,000 --> 02:08:34,000
I couldn't have carried on with the same momentum and resources for a full four year term.

1014
02:08:34,000 --> 02:08:47,000
And so in some ways it was really gratuitous that they recalled me after two and a half years because I had a tough struggle to carry on the kind of momentum.

1015
02:08:47,000 --> 02:08:55,000
And so when they completed the recall I had to decide do I want to stay out here in the Bay Area and practice law?

1016
02:08:55,000 --> 02:08:59,000
Do I want to go somewhere else? That's when I made the decision to retire in Dmitris.

1017
02:08:59,000 --> 02:09:05,000
And in that limited time the two and a half years you were able to achieve some change to the change last.

1018
02:09:05,000 --> 02:09:09,000
Did you stay in touch and see if some of that change persisted in Berkeley, California?

1019
02:09:09,000 --> 02:09:20,000
Much of it did. For example we set the pattern of an integrated city hall with the top level staff people that continued.

1020
02:09:20,000 --> 02:09:25,000
And as the same thing as opportunities in the police and fire departments that continued.

1021
02:09:25,000 --> 02:09:30,000
I took the lead and helping give the garbage workers increased benefits.

1022
02:09:30,000 --> 02:09:41,000
What happened was that there was a strike and we had an executive session told our negotiator to offer the union more money for the lower paid workers who were the garbage workers.

1023
02:09:41,000 --> 02:09:46,000
But that didn't get conveyed to the garbage workers in the negotiations.

1024
02:09:46,000 --> 02:09:55,000
And so they went on strike and so there was an impasse and Kurt McLean who was a black union leader in the Bay Area came to me and said,

1025
02:09:55,000 --> 02:09:59,000
you need to take some leadership and call for a resumption to talk.

1026
02:09:59,000 --> 02:10:09,000
And so I did. I said I'm going to show up at the negotiating table and I'm asking the union and the garbage workers to do the same, which they did.

1027
02:10:09,000 --> 02:10:16,000
And we recommenced the negotiations and two of the other council members joined me.

1028
02:10:16,000 --> 02:10:27,000
Well, when we started again we were getting nowhere fast and I called the garbage workers leaders aside and I said, look let's go talk.

1029
02:10:27,000 --> 02:10:35,000
And I took them into a side room and I said to them, look, do you realize that we're offering you guys an accelerated increase versus these other guys?

1030
02:10:35,000 --> 02:10:42,000
Because the only people there were on strike were the garbage workers but the negotiations were for all of the municipal unions.

1031
02:10:42,000 --> 02:10:50,000
Police, fire and engineers and everybody else. They were riding on the backs of the garbage workers who were on strike.

1032
02:10:50,000 --> 02:10:56,000
And I told those workers, look, if we go ahead and settle this thing, you'll get more money.

1033
02:10:56,000 --> 02:11:02,000
And because we were trying to raise them to a level on a palm with these other city employees, which we did.

1034
02:11:02,000 --> 02:11:23,000
And so that came because of that. Well, because when we got to garbage workers, when I pulled their coat out and let them know what was happening and they decided that they weren't going to carry these other unions, Paul Vericalli was the head of the union negotiating for all of them, but he was, he had divided all these there, tough union man.

1035
02:11:23,000 --> 02:11:45,000
So anyway, those kind of things were changes that we brought about. Now what has changed since then is the gentrification that in those areas now were blacks lived and what we call the flatlands nearest to the river, to the bay.

1036
02:11:45,000 --> 02:12:01,000
And now areas that are largely gentrified where you have, instead of black families living in those areas now, you have a much greater proportion of income whites because the land is so expensive.

1037
02:12:01,000 --> 02:12:14,000
And those blacks have sold out many of them so their property and move elsewhere. And so the black population of Berkeley, California has declined substantially from the 25% when I was there.

1038
02:12:14,000 --> 02:12:26,000
You know, I was going to be traveling in Berkeley, California, I was an old man. Yeah, I mean, it could be impossible to afford it.

1039
02:12:26,000 --> 02:12:49,000
So we're going to jump to Memphis. I wanted to ask about, especially since the anniversaries are happening or coming up about the Civil Rights Act and the Voting Rights Act, and where were you at the time of those pieces of national legislation and what your reaction was?

1040
02:12:49,000 --> 02:13:09,000
Give me the year because there was so much happening. 63 and 64. Okay. 64. I was still at clock because I remember as the President Kennedy was assassinated in November of 63.

1041
02:13:09,000 --> 02:13:20,000
And it was in the wake of the assassination of President Kennedy that Lyndon B. Johnson took the leadership and gave great momentum to the thrust to pass that legislation.

1042
02:13:20,000 --> 02:13:33,000
And I remember him in 65 pushing for the Voting Rights Act. And that was in the wake of Selma and the killing of Viola Liuzzo and Reverend James Reeb.

1043
02:13:33,000 --> 02:13:50,000
And I remember watching him on television when he was announcing his support for that and said, we shall overcome. And when I was sitting there watching this white Southern President in his Southern accent, say we shall overcome.

1044
02:13:50,000 --> 02:14:01,000
But not just say it, but mean it in terms of putting the weight of the presidency behind getting this legislation passed in 65.

1045
02:14:01,000 --> 02:14:24,000
I knew the things that changed in America. I mean with Johnson. Kennedy had been in many ways viewed as the hero, but the real difference came with the shoulder to the wheel work that Lyndon B. Johnson did after the assassination to get that legislation through the Congress.

1046
02:14:24,000 --> 02:14:51,000
And with the passage of the Voting Rights Act, I did not feel that the act itself was going to make a momentous change because having seen in Memphis that blacks had to vote but still no money and no power.

1047
02:14:51,000 --> 02:15:05,000
And I remember that when all was said done, give them the vote. But what does that mean in terms of fundamental change? And I never really thought and still don't think for that matter.

1048
02:15:05,000 --> 02:15:20,000
That voting power, political power, is the be all and end all of the quest for liberation. It is a tool. When I ran for the Berkeley, California City Council, it was not based upon my belief that

1049
02:15:20,000 --> 02:15:32,000
the system works. Now the media treated it that way. They said, oh, the radicals have now gone within the system. And they now believe in the system and are going to make the system work.

1050
02:15:32,000 --> 02:15:40,000
After our election in Berkeley, California, some young people ran in Madison, Wisconsin, and were elected on progressive platform.

1051
02:15:40,000 --> 02:15:57,000
And others of our generation began to mimic this whole notion that we in the Bay Area had developed. And a lot of that was through the strategy and the philosophies refined by the April coalition, the hard work that they had done and said in the past.

1052
02:15:57,000 --> 02:16:12,000
We just helped to bring it about in a victorious way. But I didn't, to me, it was opportunities as opposed to believe in the ongoing

1053
02:16:12,000 --> 02:16:31,000
and the ability of established political systems to make a difference. So I never looked at the beating of heads in the street and they're going to jail. Those were the things that I knew made a difference that would cause change in this country.

1054
02:16:31,000 --> 02:16:59,000
The riots and Watts (riots, August 1965) + Detroit + Newark and in Newark. When people take to the streets and really confront those in authority and bring things to hold. And that was my strategy in Berkeley, California. Now, of course, you have to recognize that those strategies are not lasting. In other words, you've got to be prepared to move from one arena to the other.

1055
02:16:59,000 --> 02:17:15,000
If you think that you can take one strategy and stand fast on that strategy and carry forth the progress, then you're in for rude awakening because you've got to be run over. And so you've got to know when the songs and no one to hold them and no one to hold them.

1056
02:17:15,000 --> 02:17:36,000
Because they'll eventually figure out how to neutralize what you're doing. But in the meantime, you can make dramatic difference. But the system is not going to change because the political system is basically designed to be used and controlled by the money, power of the country.

1057
02:17:36,000 --> 02:17:57,000
Because it's money that you have to have the run for office and to stay in office. And then the communities that you're trying to reach, you have to reach to mechanisms that are controlled by money, communications. And right on down to the workforce. And they've decimated unions. And so you don't have a labor voice that can kind of offset.

1058
02:17:57,000 --> 02:18:18,000
And now, in, for example, states like Tennessee, where politics means very little because we've got super majorities in the legislature and a Republican president. And they are now, they are vulcanized in the country with strongholds of right wing power.

1059
02:18:18,000 --> 02:18:28,000
And I'm not sure, but that in time, the growth of that power will not again become a majority power in America.

1060
02:18:30,000 --> 02:18:47,000
I mean, this is why, yeah, this is what, this is what we're up against. But it's also, I mean, as you say, why a movement needs to be multifaceted. You need to have these fronts. You need to have the judicial front and the WACP and the same time that you have SNCC and protest in the streets.

1061
02:18:47,000 --> 02:19:02,000
And I spent 19 years as a, as a trial judge here in Memphis, and 14 additional years as a lawyer, doing which I represent people who were charged with murder and were facing death penalty.

1062
02:19:02,000 --> 02:19:15,000
I've tried over a dozen capital cases where my client was facing the chair. And in those cases, I had to work within the system to try to get justice for my client.

1063
02:19:15,000 --> 02:19:28,000
I was almost to say I had to thwart the system because lawyers within the judicial system are not looking for justice. We look for victory for our side.

1064
02:19:28,000 --> 02:19:34,000
And that's true. If you're planning for lawyer or you're a defense lawyer or if you represent the prosecution or the defense.

1065
02:19:34,000 --> 02:19:50,000
When I was representing people facing the chair, justice may have been that, if I'm not, I'm not a believer in capital punishment, but it may have been the many long years in the penetrator.

1066
02:19:50,000 --> 02:20:03,000
But if I got someone off with fewer know years, then to me that was gratifying victory because that was my job not to have a just result.

1067
02:20:03,000 --> 02:20:16,000
As a judge, however, for 19 years, my role was quite different. It was to assure that the system at least was a level playing field for all sides within that arena.

1068
02:20:16,000 --> 02:20:35,000
But I never felt even then that the legal system is a system set up for fundamental justice. It's a system by which you could order disputes and set the rules by which to resolve disputes where people don't have to resort to violence.

1069
02:20:35,000 --> 02:20:39,000
And maybe tweak it here and there to make it a little more just.

1070
02:20:39,000 --> 02:20:56,000
Yes, but then when you think about it and we look at the legal system, I remember William Kunstler and Arthur Kinoy who came to Memphis when we were open in the Civil Rights Museum in 1991.

1071
02:20:56,000 --> 02:21:21,000
And those were two of the premier lawyers and the civil liberties and civil rights struggle. And at that time, they were arguing in their presentations to the groups there that lawyers and activists should take their pleas now to state courts and state systems because the federal system was then federal courts were not responding.

1072
02:21:21,000 --> 02:21:33,000
And so it was a matter of where do you fight? Do you fight on the state level? Do you fight on the federal level? It's not that you have any great affinity for either as it relates to change.

1073
02:21:33,000 --> 02:22:00,000
So now the kind of advocacy that may have been developed to go into the state systems and fight there or even in the 1960s to go into the federal systems and fight, well now we can't go into the federal system and fight because you've got a Supreme Court with a majority that has no sympathy for the change that people need and are fighting for.

1074
02:22:00,000 --> 02:22:17,000
And while you do have some federal appeals courts that are more sympathetic, many of them are not. And on the trial court level in the federal system, you may or may not get a good conscience judge.

1075
02:22:17,000 --> 02:22:41,000
So while in the past, we could say that the judiciary is a means of change. But if you look at what's happening with them, with the changes they're making on the Citizens United v. FEC, where they're letting corporations now have complete ownership of the communications and electoral machinery that makes a difference in this country with unlimited money.

1076
02:22:42,000 --> 02:23:07,000
Then the judiciary is open in the way for that. The Bush v. Gore decision, which was a coup d'etat, judicial coup d'etat against the will of the majority of the people. And then I saw Justice Antonin Scalia, say on television, within the last year or so, where people need to just quote, get over it.

1077
02:23:07,000 --> 02:23:14,000
And so that's kind of the judicial attitude. So getting the voting rights act.

1078
02:23:14,000 --> 02:23:29,000
Yes. And so you just have to look at, well, where do we turn to now? And in some ways, we're just as desperate. I mean, there's some of us a little bit of off.

1079
02:23:29,000 --> 02:23:43,000
We've got a few more material things. We've got educationally. There's a decline in the number of African Americans, for example, proportionally that it get into the major colleges and universities.

1080
02:23:43,000 --> 02:23:57,000
When I was coming up, we had at least the idealism that one generation would be a step better in its hard work and achievements than our parents. But that's no longer the case.

1081
02:23:57,000 --> 02:24:22,000
And so I tend to sometimes use the analogy of Hegel's dialectic, in which there's a notion that there's a cycle and that things calm down. And then in the calm oppression makes its raises its head again. And injustice gets worse that people then rebel.

1082
02:24:22,000 --> 02:24:37,000
And out of that rebellion, you get progress and change. And there's a continuing cycle of the thesis things as they are, the antithesis, when people revolt and the synthesis, some progress comes and things get bad again.

1083
02:24:37,000 --> 02:24:52,000
And so as it relates to the Voting Rights Act in 65, as it relates to the Civil Rights Act, the Public Commodation Act, those things were important changes. And they were important landmarks.

1084
02:24:52,000 --> 02:25:20,000
But they never struck me as being major game changers. Even when Title VII, Fair Employment, Equal Employment Opportunities Commission, and was passed in the 64, became effective in 65, I was never so naive to think that we were truly going to see the elimination of racism and employment opportunities in this country.

1085
02:25:20,000 --> 02:25:31,000
And we don't see it even today. The barriers are different. I mean, they're not outright racial in the same way, but the result is the same.

